# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: defense-sports
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Varieties of American English include many patterns of pronunciation, vocabulary, grammar, and particularly spelling that are unified nationwide but distinct from other forms of English around the world.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] However, historical and present linguistic evidence does not support the notion of there being one single mainstream American accent.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The sound of American English continues to evolve, with some local accents disappearing, but several larger regional accents having emerged in the 20th century.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The use of English in the United States is a result of British colonization of the Americas.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The first wave of English-speaking settlers arrived in North America during the early 17th century, followed by further migrations in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] English thus predominated in the colonies even by the end of the 17th century's first immigration of non-English speakers from Western Europe and Africa.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Firsthand descriptions of a fairly uniform American English (particularly in contrast to the diverse regional dialects of British English) became common after the mid-18th century, while at the same time speakers' identification with this new variety increased.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Since the 18th century, American English has developed into some new varieties, including regional dialects that retain minor influences from waves of immigrant speakers of diverse languages, primarily European languages.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Some racial and regional variation in American English reflects these groups' patterns of geographic settlement, segregation, and resettlement.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] This can be seen, for example, in the influence of 18th-century Protestant Ulster Scots immigrants (known in the U.S. as the Scotch-Irish) in Appalachia developing Appalachian English and the 20th-century Great Migration bringing African-American Vernacular English to the Great Lakes urban centers.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Most American English accents fall under an umbrella known as General American.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Rather than one particular accent, General American is a spectrum of those American accents that Americans themselves do not associate with some particular region, ethnicity, or socioeconomic group.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] General American features are used most by Americans in formal contexts or who are highly educated.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Regional accents whose native features are perceived as General American include the accents of the North Midland (parts of the Midwest), Western New England, and the West.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The General American sound system's scope of influence and degree of expansion has been debated by linguists since the term was first used roughly a century ago.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Many late-20th and early-21st century studies are showing that it is gradually ousting the regional accents in urban areas of the South and the interior North, New York City, Philadelphia, and many other areas.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] It can generally be said that younger Americans are avoiding their traditional local features in favor of this more nationwide norm.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Furthermore, even General American itself appears to be evolving, with linguists identifying new features in speakers born since the last quarter of the 20th century, like a merger of the low-back vowels and a potentially related vowel shift, that are spreading across the nation.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Like many British accents, T glottalization is the norm in American accents, though only in particular environments (with *satin* pronounced [ˈsæʔn̩], not [ˈsætn̩]).
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Specifically, the LOT–PALM merger is complete among most Americans and the LOT–THOUGHT merger among roughly half.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] A three-way LOT–PALM–THOUGHT merger is also very common, meaning that words like *baht*, *bot*, and *bought* are all homophones.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Most Americans pronounce the diphthong /aɪ/ before a voiceless consonant different from that same vowel before a voiced consonant: thus, in *price* and *bright* versus in *prize* and *bride*.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] For many, outside the South, the first element of the diphthong is a higher and shorter vowel sound when in pre-voiceless position as opposed to pre-voiced position.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] All of these phenomena are explained in further detail under General American.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Unlike American accents, the traditional standard accent of (southern) England has evolved a *trap–bath* split.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Moreover, American accents preserve /h/ at the start of syllables, while perhaps a majority of the regional dialects of England participate in /h/ dropping, particularly in informal contexts.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The process of developing new lexical items began as soon as British English-speaking colonists in North America began borrowing names for unfamiliar flora, fauna, and topography from the Native American languages.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Examples of such names are *opossum, raccoon, squash*, *moose* (from Algonquian), *wigwam*, and *moccasin*.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] American English speakers have integrated traditionally non-English terms and expressions into the mainstream cultural lexicon; for instance, *en masse*, from French; *cookie*, from Dutch; *kindergarten* from German, and *rodeo* from Spanish.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Landscape features are often loanwords from French or Spanish, and the word *corn*, used in England to refer to wheat (or any cereal), came to denote the maize plant, the most important crop in the U.S.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Other common differences between UK and American English include: *aerial* (UK) vs.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] *apartment*, *fringe* (UK; for hair hanging over the forehead) vs.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Most Mexican Spanish contributions came after the War of 1812, with the opening of the West, like *ranch* (now a common house style).
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Due to Mexican culinary influence, many Spanish words are incorporated in general use when talking about certain popular dishes: cilantro (instead of coriander), queso, tacos, quesadillas, enchiladas, tostadas, fajitas, burritos, and guacamole.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] These words usually lack an English equivalent and are found in popular restaurants.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] New forms of dwelling created new terms *(lot, waterfront)* and types of homes like *log cabin, adobe* in the 18th century; *apartment, shanty* in the 19th century; *project, condominium, townhouse, mobile home* in the 20th century; and parts thereof *(driveway, breezeway, backyard)*.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Already existing English words—such as *store, shop, lumber*—underwent shifts in meaning; others remained in the U.S. while changing in Britain.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Science, urbanization, and democracy have been important factors in bringing about changes in the written and spoken language of the United States.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] From the world of business and finance came new terms (*merger, downsize, bottom line*), from sports and gambling terminology came, specific jargon aside, common everyday American idioms, including many idioms related to baseball.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The names of some American inventions remained largely confined to North America (*elevator* [except in the aeronautical sense], *gasoline*) as did certain automotive terms (*truck*, *trunk*).
[src:defense-sports/american-english] New foreign loanwords came with 19th and early 20th century European immigration to the U.S.; notably, from Yiddish *(chutzpah, schmooze, bupkis, glitch*) and German (*hamburger, wiener*).
[src:defense-sports/american-english] American English has always shown a marked tendency to use words in different parts of speech and nouns are often used as verbs.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Examples of nouns that are now also verbs are *interview, advocate, vacuum, lobby, pressure, rear-end, transition, feature, profile, hashtag, head, divorce, loan, estimate, X-ray, spearhead, skyrocket, showcase, bad-mouth, vacation, major,* and many others.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Compounds coined in the U.S. are for instance *foothill, landslide* (in all senses), *backdrop, teenager,* *brainstorm, bandwagon, hitchhike, smalltime,* and a huge number of others.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Other compound words have been founded based on industrialization and the wave of the automobile: five-passenger car, four-door sedan, two-door sedan, and station-wagon (called an estate car in British English).
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Some are euphemistic *(human resources, affirmative action, correctional facility).* Many compound nouns have the verb-and-preposition combination: *stopover, lineup, tryout, spin-off, shootout, holdup, hideout, comeback, makeover,* and many more.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Some prepositional and phrasal verbs are in fact of American origin (*win out, hold up, back up/off/down/out, face up to* and many others).
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Noun endings such as *-ee (retiree), -ery (bakery), -ster (gangster)* and *-cian (beautician)* are also particularly productive in the U.S.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] A number of words and meanings that originated in Middle English or Early Modern English and that have been in everyday use in the United States have since disappeared in most varieties of British English; some of these have cognates in Lowland Scots.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Terms such as *fall* ("autumn"), *faucet* ("tap"), *diaper* ("nappy"; itself unused in the U.S.), *candy* ("sweets"), *skillet*, *eyeglasses*, and *obligate* are often regarded as Americanisms.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] *Fall*, however, came to denote the season in 16th century England, a contraction of Middle English expressions like "fall of the leaf" and "fall of the year".
[src:defense-sports/american-english] *Gotten* (past participle of *get*) is often considered to be largely an Americanism.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Other words and meanings were brought back to Britain from the U.S., especially in the second half of the 20th century; these include *hire* ("to employ"), *I guess* (famously criticized by H.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Fowler), *baggage*, *hit* (a place), and the adverbs *overly* and *presently* ("currently").
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Some of these, for example, *monkey wrench* and *wastebasket*, originated in 19th century Britain.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The adjectives *mad* meaning "angry", *smart* meaning "intelligent", and *sick* meaning "ill" are also more frequent in American (and Irish) English than British English.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Linguist Bert Vaux created a survey, completed in 2003, polling English speakers across the United States about their specific everyday word choices, hoping to identify regionalisms.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] American English and British English (BrE) differ in relatively minor ways in their grammar and writing conventions.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The first large American dictionary, *An American Dictionary of the English Language*, known as Webster's Dictionary, was written by Noah Webster in 1828, codifying several of these spellings.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Often, these differences are a matter of relative preferences rather than absolute rules; and most are not stable since the two varieties are constantly influencing each other, and American English is not a standardized set of dialects.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Differences in orthography are also minor.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The main differences are that American English usually uses spellings such as *flavor* for British *flavour*, *fiber* for *fibre*, *defense* for *defence*, *analyze* for *analyse*, *license* for *licence*, *catalog* for *catalogue* and *traveling* for *travelling*.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Noah Webster popularized such spellings in America, but he did not invent most of them.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] AmE almost always uses *-ize* in words like *realize*.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] BrE prefers *-ise*, but also uses *-ize* on occasion (see: Oxford spelling).
[src:defense-sports/american-english] There are a few differences in punctuation rules.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] British English is more tolerant of run-on sentences, called "comma splices" in American English, and American English prefers that periods and commas be placed inside closing quotation marks even in cases in which British rules would place them outside.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] American English also favors the double quotation mark ("like this") over the single ('as here').
[src:defense-sports/american-english] AmE sometimes favors words that are morphologically more complex, whereas BrE uses clipped forms, such as AmE *transportation* and BrE *transport* or where the British form is a back-formation, such as AmE *burglarize* and BrE *burgle* (from *burglar*).
[src:defense-sports/american-english] However, while individuals usually use one or the other, both forms will be widely understood and mostly used alongside each other within the two systems.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] as well as the related Telsur Project's regional maps.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Any region may also contain speakers of a "General American" accent that resists the marked features of their region.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The regional sounds of present-day American English are reportedly engaged in a complex phenomenon of "both convergence and divergence": some accents are homogenizing and leveling, while others are diversifying and deviating further away from one another.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] As of the 20th century, the middle and eastern Great Lakes area, Chicago being the largest city with these speakers, also ushered in certain unique features, including the fronting of the LOT /ɑ/ vowel in the mouth toward [a] and tensing of the TRAP /æ/ vowel wholesale to [eə].
[src:defense-sports/american-english] These sound changes have triggered a series of other vowel shifts in the same region, known by linguists as the "Inland North".
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The Inland North shares with the Eastern New England dialect (including Boston accents) a backer tongue positioning of the GOOSE /u/ vowel (to [u]) and the MOUTH /aʊ/ vowel (to [ɑʊ~äʊ]) in comparison to the rest of the country.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Ranging from northern New England across the Great Lakes to Minnesota, another Northern regional marker is the variable fronting of /ɑ/ before /r/, for example, appearing four times in the stereotypical Boston shibboleth *Park the car in Harvard Yard*.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Several other phenomena serve to distinguish regional American accents.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Boston, Pittsburgh, Upper Midwestern, and Western U.S. accents have fully completed a merger of the LOT vowel with the THOUGHT vowel (/ɑ/ and /ɔ/, respectively): a *cot–caught* merger, which is rapidly spreading throughout the whole country.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] However, the South, Inland North, and a Northeastern coastal corridor passing through Rhode Island, New York City, Philadelphia, and Baltimore typically preserve an older *cot–caught* distinction.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] For that Northeastern corridor, the realization of the THOUGHT vowel is particularly marked, as depicted in humorous spellings, like in *tawk* and *cawfee* (*talk* and *coffee*), which intend to represent it being tense and diphthongal: [oə].
[src:defense-sports/american-english] A split of TRAP into two separate phonemes, using different *a* pronunciations for example in *gap* [æ] versus *gas* [eə], further defines New York City as well as Philadelphia–Baltimore accents.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Most Americans preserve all historical /r/ sounds, using what is known as a rhotic accent.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Non-rhoticity makes a word like *car* sound like *cah* or *source* like *sauce*.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] New York City and Southern accents are the most widely recognized regional accents in the country, as well as the most stigmatized and socially disfavored.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The fronting of the vowels of GOOSE, GOAT, MOUTH, and STRUT tends to also define Southern accents as well as the accents spoken in the "Midland": a vast band of the country that constitutes an intermediate dialect region between the traditional North and South.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Western U.S. accents mostly fall under the General American spectrum.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Although no longer region-specific, African-American Vernacular English, which remains the native variety of most working- and middle-class African Americans, has a close relationship to Southern dialects and has greatly influenced everyday speech of many Americans, including hip hop culture.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Hispanic and Latino Americans have also developed native-speaker varieties of English.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The best-studied Latino Englishes are Chicano English, spoken in the West and Midwest, and New York Latino English, spoken in the New York metropolitan area.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Additionally, ethnic varieties such as Yeshiva English and "Yinglish" are spoken by some American Orthodox Jews, Cajun Vernacular English by some Cajuns in southern Louisiana, and Pennsylvania Dutch English by some Pennsylvania Dutch people.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] American Indian Englishes have been documented among diverse Indian tribes.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] The island state of Hawaii, though primarily English-speaking, is also home to a creole language known commonly as Hawaiian Pidgin, and some Hawaii residents speak English with a Pidgin-influenced accent.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] In 2024, about 247.7 million Americans, aged five or above, spoke English at home, a majority (77%) of the total U.S. population aged five and over.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Of the 50 states, 32 have adopted legislation granting official (or co-official) status to English within their jurisdictions, in some cases as part of what has been called the English-only movement.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Typically only "English" is specified, not a particular variety like American English.
[src:defense-sports/american-english] Puerto Rico is the only United States territory in which another language – Spanish – is the common language at home, in public, and in government.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] In American football, the specific role that a player takes on the field is referred to as their position.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Under the modern rules of American football, both teams are allowed 11 players on the field at one time and have "unlimited free substitutions", meaning that they may change any number of players during any dead ball situation.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Within these three separate platoons, various positions exist depending on the jobs that the players are doing.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] In American football, the offense is the team that has possession of the ball and is advancing toward the opponent's end zone to score points.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The rules of the sport strictly mandate the organization of the offense: there must be at least seven players on the line of scrimmage and no more than four players, known collectively as backs, behind it.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The only players eligible to handle the ball during a normal play are the backs and the two players on the ends of the line, known as the ends.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] These players make up the skill positions and are also referred to as eligible receivers or eligible ball carriers.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The remaining players, known as interior linemen, are ineligible to catch forward passes.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Within these structures, however, creative coaches have developed a wide array of offensive formations to take advantage of different player skills and game situations.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The following positions are standard in nearly every game, though different teams will use different arrangements of them, depending on their individual game plans.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The offensive line is primarily responsible for blocking the defensive line of the opposition to protect their own quarterback.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] During normal play, offensive linemen do not handle the ball (aside from the snap from center) unless the ball is fumbled by a ball carrier, a pass is deflected, or a player who is normally an offensive lineman takes a different position on the field.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The center is the player who begins the play from scrimmage by snapping the ball to the quarterback.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] As the name suggests, the center usually plays in the middle of the offensive line, though some teams may employ an unbalanced line where the center is offset to one side.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Like all offensive linemen, the center has the responsibility to block defensive players.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The center often also has the responsibility to call out blocking assignments and make last-second adjustments depending on the defensive alignment.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Two guards line up directly on opposite sides of the center.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Like all interior linemen, their function is to block on both running and passing plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] On some plays, rather than blocking straight ahead, a guard will pull, during which the guard comes out of their position in line to lead block for a ball carrier, on plays known as traps (for inside runs), sweeps for outside runs, and screens for passing plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] In such cases, the guard is referred to as a pulling guard.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Their role is primarily to block on both running and passing plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The area from one tackle to the other is an area of close line play in which blocks from behind, which are prohibited elsewhere on the field, are allowed.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] For a right-handed quarterback, the left tackle is charged with protecting the quarterback from being hit from behind, known as the blind side, and this is usually the most skilled player on the offensive line.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Like a guard, the tackle may have to pull on a running play when there is a tight end on their side.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Tackles typically have a taller, longer build than interior offensive linemen, due to the need to keep separation from defensive linemen in pass blocking situations.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] They also tend to have quick footwork skills, often engaging against containing or rushing defensive ends.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Offensive positions that handle the ball and are primarily responsible for advancing yards and scoring points are known as the skill positions.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] They include quarterbacks, backs, wide receivers, and tight ends.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The quarterback is the player who receives the ball from the center to start the play.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The quarterback may need to make late changes to the intended play at the line of scrimmage, known as an audible, depending on the defensive alignment.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] At the start of the play, the quarterback may be lined up in one of three positions.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] If they are positioned directly behind and in contact with the center and receive the ball via the direct hand-to-hand pass, they are said to be "under center".
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Alternatively, if they are lined up some distance behind the center, they are said to be either in shotgun formation or in pistol formation, with shotgun generally further back than pistol.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Upon receiving the ball from the center, the quarterback has three basic options to advance the ball: they may run the ball themself (commonly referred to as scrambling), hand it to another eligible ball carrier to run with it, or execute a forward pass to a player further up the field.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Running backs are players who line up behind the offensive line in a position to receive a hand-off from the quarterback and execute a rushing play.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Anywhere from zero to three running backs may be utilized on a play; a formation with no running backs is often called an empty backfield.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Depending on where they line up and what role they have, running backs come in several varieties.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The tailback, also known as the halfback, is often a team's primary ball carrier on rushing plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] They may also catch passes, often acting as a check-down or safety valve when all other receivers on a pass play are covered.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] A wing-back or a slot-back is a term for a running back who lines up behind the line of scrimmage outside the tackle or tight end on either side of the offensive line.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Slot-backs are usually only found in certain offensive alignments, such as the [flexbone formation].
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] There also exists a similar position, known as the [H-back], which is actually considered a modification of the normal tight end position.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The fullback is often larger and stronger than the tailback and acts primarily as a blocker, though the fullback may also be used for catching passes or for rushing as a tailback does.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Fullbacks often line up closer to the line of scrimmage than tailbacks do to block for them on rushing plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Wide receivers are pass-catching specialists.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Typically fast and tall, their main job is to run pass routes and get open (i.e, find a position with no nearby defender) for passes, although they are occasionally utilized as blockers.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Wide receivers generally line up split wide near the sidelines at the start of the play.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Wide receivers, like running backs, come in different varieties depending on exactly where they line up.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] A wide receiver who is directly on the line of scrimmage is called a split end and is counted among the seven required players on the line of scrimmage.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] A wide receiver who lines up behind the line and counts as one of the four backs is called the flanker.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] A wide receiver who lines up between the outermost wide receiver and the offensive line is said to be in the slot and is called the slot receiver.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] A wide receiver who can play running back is called a wide back.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Tight ends play on either side of the offensive line and directly next to the tackles.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Tight ends are considered hybrid players because they are a cross between a wide receiver and an offensive lineman.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Because they play next to the other offensive linemen, they are very frequently called on to block, especially on run plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] However, because they are eligible receivers, they may also catch passes.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The position known as the H-back is a tight end who lines up behind the line of scrimmage, and is thus counted as one of the four backs, but their role is otherwise similar to that of other tight ends.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Depending on the style of offense the coaches have designed, the game situation, and the relative skill sets of the players, teams may run formations that contain any number of running backs, wide receivers, and tight ends, so long as the mandated four backs and seven on the line rule is followed.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] For many years, the standard set consisted of the quarterback, two running backs (a tailback/halfback and a fullback), two wide receivers (a flanker and a split end), and a tight end.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Modern teams show a wide variety of formations, from a full house formation with three running backs, two tight ends, and no wide receivers, to spread formations featuring four or five wide receivers and either one or no running backs.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The defensive team, simply known as the defense, is the team that begins a play from scrimmage without possession of the ball.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The objective of the defensive team is to prevent the other team from scoring and win possession of the ball for their side.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The defense accomplishes this by forcing the offense to turn the ball over by either preventing them from achieving a first down and forcing them to punt, forcing and recovering an offensive fumble, intercepting a pass, or more rarely, forcing a turnover on downs.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Unlike the offensive team, the rules of the sport do not restrict the defensive team to certain positions.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] A defensive player may line up anywhere on his side of the line of scrimmage and perform any legal action.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Over time, however, defensive roles have become defined into three main sets of players that encompass several individual positions.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Defensive formations are often known by a numerical code indicating the number of players at each position.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The two most common formations are the 3–4 defense and the 4–3 defense, where the first number refers to the number of defensive linemen, and the second number refers to the number of linebackers (the number of defensive backs can be inferred, since there must be eleven players on the field).
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Thus, a 3–4 defense consists of three defensive linemen (usually a nose tackle and two defensive ends), four linebackers, and four defensive backs (two cornerbacks, a strong safety, and a free safety).
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Some defensive formations will directly indicate the number of defensive backs.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The 3–3–5 defense, for instance, has 3 defensive linemen, 3 linebackers, and 5 defensive backs.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Like their offensive counterparts, defensive linemen (also called rushers) line up directly on the line of scrimmage.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Sometimes called a defensive guard, defensive tackles play at the center of the defensive line.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Their function is to rush the passer and stop running plays directed at the middle of the line of scrimmage.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Most defensive sets have one or two defensive tackles.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] If one employs a second defensive tackle, sometimes referred to as an under tackle, they are usually a bit faster than the nose tackle.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Sometimes called a middle guard or nose guard, nose tackles play in the center of the defensive line.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Their function is to clog the middle of the offensive line and stop most run plays (most commonly fullback dives, plunges, and sneaks).
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] They line up directly in front of the offense's center, almost nose-to-nose, hence the name.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] This position is used in 3-4 formations or goal-line situations.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Most nose tackles are 320-350 pounds, and are the biggest players on the roster.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] This position is the most physically demanding, as players are often forced into constant double or triple teams and need enough speed to collapse the interior of the offensive line.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Sometimes, nose tackles are used in 4-3 defenses and are either positioned on the quarterback's blind side or directly in front of the center.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Defensive ends line up outside of the defensive tackles and are the ends of the defensive line.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Their function is to attack the passer or stop offensive runs to the outer edges of the line of scrimmage, which is often referred to as containment.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The faster of the two is usually placed on the right side of the defensive line (quarterback's left) because that is the right-handed quarterback's blind side.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Defensive linemen will often take a stance with one or both of their hands on the ground before the ball is snapped.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] These are known as a three-point stance and four-point stance, respectively, and this helps distinguish a defensive lineman from a linebacker, who begins in a two-point stance (i.e., without a hand touching the ground).
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Linebackers play behind the defensive line and perform various duties depending on the situation, including rushing the passer, covering receivers, and defending against the run.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Sometimes called the inside linebacker, especially in a 3–4 defense, and known colloquially as the Mike linebacker, the middle linebacker is often known as the quarterback of the defense, since they are frequently the primary defensive play callers and must react to a wide variety of situations.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Middle linebackers must be capable of stopping running backs who make it past the defensive line, covering pass plays over the middle, and rushing the quarterback on blitz plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] An outside linebacker is a versatile "hybrid" athlete who plays on the edges of the defense to stop the offense from moving outside.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Their first job is to "set the edge," acting like a wall that forces the runner back toward the middle of the field.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] On passing plays, they either blitz the quarterback to get a sack or drop back into space to guard receivers like tight ends.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Because they have to be strong enough to hit and fast enough to run, they are basically the "Swiss Army Knife" of the football team.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Defensive backs, also known as the secondary, play either behind the linebackers or outside near the sidelines and are primarily used to defend against pass plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] They also act as the last line of defense on running plays and need to be able to make open field tackles, especially when the ball carrier has gotten past the other defenders.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] A normal defensive lineup includes two cornerbacks and two safeties.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] However, specialty defensive backs (nickelbacks and dime backs) can be brought in in place of linebackers and defensive linemen when there is a need to cover additional receivers.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Cornerbacks attempt to prevent successful passes by either swatting the airborne ball away from the receiver or by catching the pass themselves.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] In rushing situations, their job is to contain the runner, either by directing them back to the middle of the field to be tackled by the middle line backers or by forcing them out of bounds.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] In certain formations, the defense may remove a linebacker or a defensive lineman to bring in extra pass coverage in the form of extra defensive backs.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] A formation with five defensive backs is often called a nickel formation, and the fifth (extra) defensive back is called a nickelback after the U.S. nickel coin, a five-cent piece.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] By extension, a formation with a sixth defensive back, known as the dimeback, is called a dime package because it employs a second nickelback and the U.S.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] 10-cent dime coin is equal to two nickels.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Although it is a rare occurrence, a team may also use seven or eight defensive backs on a play.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The safeties are the last line of defense (farthest from the line of scrimmage) and usually help the corners with deep-pass coverage.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The *strong safety* (SS) is traditionally the larger and stronger of the two, providing extra protection against run plays by standing closer to the line of scrimmage, usually on the strong (tight end) side of the field.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The *free safety* (FS) is often the smaller and faster of the two, and is typically the deepest player on the defense, providing help on long pass plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Special teams are units that are on the field during kicking plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] While many players who appear on offensive or defensive squads also play similar roles on special teams (offensive linemen to block or defensive players to tackle), some specialist roles are unique to the kicking game.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Placekickers, colloquially called simply a kicker, handle kickoffs, extra points, and field goals.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] All three situations require the kicker to kick the ball off the ground, either from the hands of a holder or off a tee.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Some teams employ two kickers: one kicks extra points and field goals.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Most, however, use a single kicker for both jobs, and rarely, the same player may also punt.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Kickoff specialists are kickers used exclusively on kickoffs.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] In most cases, the team's regular kicker or punter performs the role.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Teams may employ pure kickoff specialists if they feel neither are good enough at kickoffs.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Due to their specialized nature and the limited number of active roster spots, kickoff specialists are rare.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The punter punts the ball to relinquish possession to the defensive team and to send the ball as far downfield as possible.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] This is usually done only on fourth down.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The punter usually lines up 15 yards behind the line of scrimmage.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] However, this distance has to be shortened when it would result in being on or behind the end line.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] After receiving the snap, the punter drops the football and kicks, or punts, it through the air.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The holder is usually positioned 7–8 yards from the line of scrimmage and holds the ball for the placekicker to kick.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The player occupying this position is often a backup quarterback or a punter because of their good hands, feel for the ball, and experience taking snaps from a long snapper or center during plays from scrimmage.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] A holder is occasionally used on kickoffs if the weather or field conditions repeatedly cause the ball to fall off the tee.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The long snapper is a specialized center who snaps the ball directly to the holder or punter.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] They are usually distinct from a regular center, as the ball often has to be snapped much further back on kicking plays than on standard offensive plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Long snappers are generally the size of tight ends or linebackers, as they not only have to be big enough to block for the punter or kicker, but also athletic enough to run down the field on coverage to try to tackle the return man.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] In the past, long snappers were often backup players; nowadays, this position is typically filled by dedicated long snappers.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Return specialists are responsible for catching kicked balls (either on kickoffs or punts) and running the ball back.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] These are usually among the fastest players on a team and typically play either wide receiver or cornerback, as well.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] However, due to the relatively high likelihood of injury during kick returns, most professional teams will not regularly use their very best WRs or CBs as returners.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Teams may also use the same player for both return positions or have a specific returner for punts and another for kickoffs.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The upback, also known as the **personal protector**, is a blocking back who lines up approximately 1–3 yards behind the line of scrimmage in punting situations.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Because the punter plays so far back, the back frequently makes the line calls and lets the long snapper know when the punter is ready to receive the ball.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Their primary role is to act as the last line of defense for the punter; however, upbacks occasionally receive the snap instead on fake punts and will either pass or run with the football in those situations.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Upbacks are usually played by backup running backs or linebackers.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] The upback, along with the punter, are usually the last lines of defense to prevent an opponent from returning a punt for a touchdown.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] A gunner is a player on kickoffs and punts who specializes in running down the field very quickly in an attempt to tackle the returner.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] They usually line up near the sidelines, where there will be fewer blockers, which allows them to get down the field quickly.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Wide receivers and cornerbacks commonly play the position.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-positions] Jammers try to slow down gunners during punts or kickoffs so the returners have more time to move down the field.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Strategy plays a crucial role in American football.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Both teams carefully plan various aspects of their gameplay in an effort to win.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] This includes deciding on formations, selecting players for specific positions, and assigning roles and instructions to each player on offense and defense.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Throughout the game, each team constantly adjusts their strategy, responding to the other's strengths and weaknesses.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] They experiment with different approaches to outmaneuver or overpower their opponent.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] On offense, a team's objective is to score through touchdowns and field goals, all while remaining vigilant of the opposing team's defensive strategy.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] On defense, the goal is to prevent the offense from scoring, as well as attempting to intercept the ball and shift momentum in their favor.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The primary goal of the offense is to score points.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] To achieve this, coaches and players design and execute plays based on several factors: the players involved, the opponent's defensive strategy, the time remaining before halftime or the end of the game, and the number of points needed to secure a win.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Offensively, teams can also aim to prolong possession of the ball to limit the opponent's scoring opportunities.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Drives, or offensive scoring chances, come to an end when the team either scores, fails to move the ball 10 yards and must punt the ball or kick a field goal, or turns it over via fumble, interception, or failing to convert on fourth down.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] On offense, there are three types of players: linemen, backs, and wide receivers.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The positions and duties of these players can vary depending on the offensive scheme used by each team.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Backs are named for their position behind the line of scrimmage at the start of a play.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Before the ball is snapped, the offensive team lines up in a formation.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The type of formation used is determined by the game situation.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Teams often employ "special formations" for specific scenarios, such as obvious passing situations, short yardage, or goal-line plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Some formations are designed for a particular game to confuse the defense.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] When the team is in formation and the quarterback gives a signal—either by calling out instructions or using a non-verbal cue known as a "silent count"—the centre snaps the ball to the quarterback, and a play begins.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] A running play occurs when the quarterback hands the ball to another player, who then attempts to carry it past the line of scrimmage to gain yards.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Alternatively, the quarterback may keep the ball and run beyond the line of scrimmage themself.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] In both scenarios, the offensive line's primary job is to run block, preventing defensive players from tackling the ball carrier.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The choice of running play depends on the offensive team’s strengths, the defensive weaknesses, and the distance required to score a touchdown or gain a first down.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] When a passing play occurs, the backs and receivers run specific patterns, or routes, while the quarterback throws the ball to one of the players.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] During these plays, the offensive line's primary job is to prevent defensive players from tackling the quarterback before he throws the ball (a "sack") or disrupting the quarterback in any other way during the play.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Passing plays generally cover more ground than running plays, making them ideal for situations where the offensive team needs to gain a large number of yards.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Even if a team does not need to gain a large number of yards, relying solely on running plays could make the offense predictable.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Run plays are often used to tire out defensive linemen and to set up passing plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] One way to set up a passing play is through a play-action pass.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] In this strategy, the quarterback and running back fake a run play while the receivers run routes.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The goal is to deceive the defense into thinking it's a run play, allowing the receivers to get open for an easier completion.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Successfully running the ball can also make play-action passes more effective, as the defense may be caught off guard, leading to bigger plays if the pass is completed.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] One general rule teams must consider when developing their passing strategy is that only certain players are allowed to catch forward passes.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] If a player who is not an eligible receiver receives a thrown pass, the team may be penalized.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] However, if a team reports to the referee before a play that a normally ineligible receiver will act as an eligible receiver for that play, that player is allowed to catch passes.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Teams use this strategy occasionally to confuse the defense or force them to pay more attention to potential pass catchers.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Using a combination of passing and running plays, the offense aims to gain the yards needed for a first down, touchdown, or field goal.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Distinct from the offensive strategies or philosophies that govern how a team moves the ball down the field—whether through downfield passes, short passes, or inside runs—are the methods used for calling plays.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] These play calling systems often developed alongside certain offensive strategies, though they can be adapted to any strategy.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The differences between these systems lie in the specific language used to communicate plays to players.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The goal of defensive strategy is to prevent the opposing offense from gaining yards and scoring points.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] This can be achieved either by stopping the offense from advancing the ball beyond the line of scrimmage or by taking the ball away from the offense (referred to as a turnover) and scoring points themselves.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] On defense, there are three types of players: linemen, linebackers, and defensive backs (also called secondary players).
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Their specific positions on the field and duties during the game vary depending on the type of defense being used and the kind of offense the defense is facing.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The defensive line lines up in front of the offensive line.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The responsibility of the defensive lineman is to prevent the offensive line from opening up running lanes for the running back or to sack the quarterback, depending on whether the play is a passing or running play.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Most of the time, defensive linemen attack the offensive line, but in some plays, they drop back into pass coverage to confuse the opposing team.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Linebackers stand behind the defensive linemen or set themselves up on the line of scrimmage.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Depending on the defensive strategy being used, a linebacker’s responsibilities can include helping to stop the run, rushing the quarterback, or dropping back in pass protection.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Defensive backs stand behind the linebackers.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Their primary responsibility is pass coverage, although they can also be involved in stopping the run or rushing the quarterback.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The most common way to describe a basic defensive formation is by stating the number of linemen followed by the number of linebackers.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The number of defensive backs is usually not mentioned, though if it is (such as in the "3–3–5"), the number typically appears after the linebackers.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Thus, the formula would be (# of linemen)–(# of linebackers)–(# of defensive backs [if stated]) in these situations.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] This naming rule does not always apply when the personnel for a certain formation are lined up in a way that changes the function of the players in the defense.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] For example, the "3–5–3" actually uses the 3–3–5 personnel but arranges the five defensive backs with "3 deep," thus grouping the other two defensive backs with the linebackers.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] On plays where the defense expects the offense to pass, emphasis is often placed on the number of defensive backs.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] In a basic 4–3 or 3–4 defense, there are four defensive backs on the field (2 cornerbacks [CB], 1 strong safety [SS], and 1 free safety [FS]).
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] When a sixth defensive back is inserted, it is known as a "dime" package (4 CB, 1 SS, 1 FS).
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] In rare instances when a seventh defensive back is inserted, it is known as a "quarter" package (5 CB, 1 SS, 1 FS or 4 CB, 2 SS, 1 FS).
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] As with offensive formations, there are many combinations that can be used to set up a defense.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Unusual defensive alignments are constantly used in an effort to neutralize a given offense's strengths.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] For example, in Super Bowl XXV, the New York Giants used a formation with two down linemen, four linebackers, and five defensive backs, a strategy that prevented their opponents, the Buffalo Bills, from completing long passes.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] In a 2004 game, the New England Patriots used no down linemen and seven linebackers for two plays against the Miami Dolphins.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The defense must wait until the ball is snapped by the opposing center before moving across the line of scrimmage or otherwise engaging any of the offensive players.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Once the opposing offense has broken their huddle and lined up in their formation, defensive players often call out instructions to each other to make last-second adjustments to the defense.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] To prevent the opposing offense from gaining yards on the ground, a defense might focus more on their run defense.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] This typically involves placing more players close to the line of scrimmage to reach the ball carrier more quickly.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] This strategy is often used when the opposing offense needs to gain only a few yards to achieve a first down or score a touchdown.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] When the defense anticipates that the opposing offense will pass the ball, they shift into pass defense.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] There are times when a defense believes that the best way to stop the offense is to rush the quarterback.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] This involves sending five or more players charging at the line of scrimmage in an attempt to tackle the quarterback before he can throw the ball or hand it off.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Any player on the defense is allowed to rush the quarterback, and many schemes have been developed over the years that involve complicated or unusual blitz "packages".
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Defensive strategies differ somewhat from offensive strategies in that, unlike offenses which have very specific, detailed plans and assignments for each player, defenses are more reactive.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Each player's general goal is to "stop the offense" by tackling the ball carrier, breaking up passing plays, taking the ball away from the offense, or sacking the quarterback.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] While precision and timing are critical to offensive strategy, defensive strategies often emphasize aggressiveness and the ability to react to plays as they develop.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Nevertheless, many defensive strategies have been developed over the years that coaches use as a framework for their general defense, making specific adjustments based on their players' capabilities and the opponent they are facing.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The special teams unit is a group of players who take the field during kickoffs, free kicks, punts, and field goal attempts.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Most football teams' special teams include one or more kickers, a long snapper (who specializes in accurate snaps over long distances), kick returners who catch and carry the ball after it is kicked by the opposing team, and blockers who defend during kicks and returns.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Most special teams are composed of players who act as backups or substitutes on the team's offensive and defensive units.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Due to the risk of injury, it is uncommon for a starting offensive or defensive player to also play on a special teams unit.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] A variety of strategic plays can be attempted during kickoffs, punts, and field goals to surprise the opposition and score points, gain yardage or first downs, or recover possession of the kicked ball.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] A kickoff occurs at the beginning of each half, overtime period (not in college), and following each touchdown, successful field goal, or safety.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] The "no punting" strategy forgoes punting altogether and instead attempts to convert on as many fourth downs as possible.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] This strategy has been implemented at Pulaski Academy, a top-ranked prep school, and has been advocated by Gregg Easterbrook in his *Tuesday Morning Quarterback* column and author Jon Wertheim.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Fourth down decisions to punt have been analysed mathematically by David Romer.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Field goals are worth one point after a scored touchdown or three points if a team opts for a field goal attempt without scoring a touchdown but is within a suitable range for the kicker.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] If the receiving team does not catch the ball, the kicking team may try to down it as close as possible to the opposing team's end zone.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] This can be achieved by either catching the ball (typically when close to the end zone to prevent a touchback) or by surrounding the ball and allowing it to roll or bounce as close as possible to the end zone without touching it.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] If the ball appears to be rolling or bouncing into the end zone, a player may run in front of the goal line to attempt to bat it down or catch it.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] If a member of the kicking team catches the ball before a member of the receiving team does, the play is blown dead by the official, and the receiving team takes possession at the spot where the ball was touched by the kicking team.
[src:defense-sports/american-football-strategy] Therefore, it is strategically important for kicking teams to get as close to the ball as possible after a punt so they can quickly tackle a returner, down the ball as near to the opposing team's end zone as possible, and, if feasible, recover the ball after a fumble to regain possession.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] The **American League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **American League** (**AL**), is the younger of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] It developed from the Western League, a minor league based in the Great Lakes states, which eventually aspired to major league status.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] It is sometimes called the **Junior Circuit** because it claimed Major League status for the 1901 season, 25 years after the formation of the National League (the "Senior Circuit").
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Since 1903, the American League champion has played in the World Series against the National League champion with only two exceptions: 1904, when the NL champion New York Giants refused to play their AL counterpart, and 1994, when a players' strike resulted in the cancellation of the Series.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Through 2025, American League teams have won 68 of the 121 World Series played since 1903.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] The New York Yankees have won 27 World Series and 41 American League titles, the most in major league history.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] The Philadelphia/Kansas City/Oakland Athletics have won the second most AL titles with 15, followed by the Boston Red Sox with 14.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and playoffs, with only the two pennant winners meeting in the World Series.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] The AL and NL also employed and trained their own umpires, who only worked regular season games in their own league.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] These differences resulted in the leagues developing slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] The American League was usually regarded as the less "traditional" league during the 20th century, a reputation most exemplified by the introduction of the designated hitter rule in 1973, which encouraged AL managers to largely abandon "smallball" tactics.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate business entities with their own presidents and management.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the American League legally merged with the National League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which now operates much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Originally a minor league known as the Western League, which existed from 1885 to 1899 with teams in mostly Great Lakes states, the league changed its name to the American League for the 1900 season and the next year developed into a second major league as a competitor to the older National League.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] This was prompted by the NL dropping four teams following the 1899 season after having absorbed its previous rival, the American Association, which disbanded in 1891 after ten seasons.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] In its early history of the late 1880s, the minor Western League struggled until 1894, when Ban Johnson became the president of the league.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Johnson pushed the league to rise to major league status, after the name change to the American League was decided in a league meeting in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at the former Republican Hotel.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] A historical marker is at the intersection of North Dr.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Drive and West Kilbourn Avenue where the hotel once stood.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] In March 1904, Johnson moved the league's headquarters from Chicago to New York.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Babe Ruth, noted as one of the most prolific hitters in Major League Baseball history, spent the majority of his career in the American League with the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] From 1973 to 2022 The American League had one notable difference versus the rival National League, as it had the designated hitter rule.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Under the rule, a team may use a batter in its lineup who is not in the field defensively, replacing the pitcher in the batting order, compared to the old rule that made it mandatory for the pitcher to bat.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] In the last two decades, the season schedule has allowed occasional interleague play.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] In 1969, the AL (and NL) were divided into East and West divisions, with a postseason playoff series for the pennant and the right to play in the World Series.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Until the late 1970s, league umpires working behind home plate wore large, balloon-style chest protectors worn outside the shirt or coat, while their colleagues in the National League wore chest protectors inside the shirt or coat.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] In 1977, new umpires (including Steve Palermo) had to wear the inside chest protector, although those on staff wearing the outside protector could continue to do so.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Most umpires made the switch to the inside protector, led by Don Denkinger in 1975 and Jim Evans the next year, although several did not, including Bill Haller, Russ Goetz, George Maloney, Bill Kunkel and Jerry Neudecker, who became the last full-time MLB umpire to use the outside protector in 1985.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] In 1998, the newly franchised Tampa Bay Devil Rays joined the league, and the Arizona Diamondbacks joined the National League: i.e., each league added a fifteenth team.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] An odd number of teams per league meant that at least one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day, or alternatively, that odd team out would have had to play an interleague game against its counterpart in the other league.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] The initial plan was to have three five-team divisions per league with inter-league play year-round—possibly as many as 30 interleague games per team each year.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] For various reasons, it soon seemed more practical to have an even number of teams in both leagues.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed to change leagues to become the National League's 16th team, moving from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers were moved from the AL East to the AL Central, making room for the Devil Rays in the East.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Even after expansion, the American League then continued with 14 teams.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] This situation changed again in 2013 when the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central division to the American League West.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] The Astros had been in the NL for 51 years since beginning as an expansion team in 1962.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Since their move, both leagues now consist of 15 teams.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] For the first 96 years, American League teams faced their National League counterparts only in exhibition games or in the World Series.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Beginning in 1997, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] As part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the designated-hitter rule was used only in games where the American League team is the home team, until the 2022 season, when the universal DH rule was implemented.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] In 2023, American League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 National League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] In 2000, the American League ended its status as a legally independent entity when the American and National Leagues were both merged into the legal entity Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:defense-sports/american-league] This left MLB as a single league, divided into two parts, also called leagues.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] This change in legal status had no effect on play, scheduling, and so forth.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] There were eight charter teams in 1901, the league's first year as a major league, and the next year the original Milwaukee Brewers (not to be confused with the current Milwaukee Brewers) moved to St.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Louis Browns, and the year after the New York Highlanders replaced the disbanded original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Those eight franchises constituted the league for 52 seasons until the Browns moved to Baltimore and took up the Orioles name.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] The first line is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] The second line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] The third line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] World Series championships are shown with a "•", American League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "#", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "^".
[src:defense-sports/american-league] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:defense-sports/american-league] The position of the American League President and National League President became honorary.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The objective of the game is to score more goals than the opposing team by moving the ball beyond the goal line into a rectangular-framed goal defended by the opponent.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Traditionally, the game has been played over two 45-minute halves, for a total match time of 90 minutes.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] With an estimated 250 million players active in over 200 countries and territories, it is the world's most popular sport.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Association football is played in accordance with the Laws of the Game, a set of rules that has been in effect since 1863 and maintained by the International Football Association Board (IFAB) since 1886.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The game is played with a football that is 68–70 cm (27–28 in) in circumference.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] When the ball is in play, the players mainly use their feet, but may also use any other part of their body, except for their hands or arms, to control, strike, or pass the ball; the head, chest, and thighs are commonly used.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Only the goalkeepers may use their hands and arms, but only within their own penalty area.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Depending on the format of the competition, an equal number of goals scored may result in a draw being declared with 1 point awarded to each team, or the game may go into extra time or a penalty shoot-out.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Internationally, association football is governed by FIFA.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Under FIFA, there are six continental confederations: AFC, CAF, CONCACAF, CONMEBOL, OFC, and UEFA.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] National associations (e.g. the FA in England, U.S.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Soccer in the United States, etc.) are responsible for managing the game in their own countries both professionally and at an amateur level, and coordinating competitions in accordance with the Laws of the Game.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The most prestigious senior international competition is the FIFA World Cup.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The men's World Cup is the most-viewed sporting event in the world, surpassing the Olympic Games.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The most prestigious competition in European club football is the UEFA Champions League, which attracts an extensive television audience worldwide.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The final of the men's Champions League is the most-watched annual sporting event in the world.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Association football is part of a family of football games that emerged from various ball games played worldwide since antiquity.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The word "association" in this term refers to the Football Association (the FA), founded in London in 1863, which published the first set of rules for the sport that same year.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The term was coined to distinguish the type of football played in accordance with the FA rules from other types that were gaining popularity at the time, particularly rugby football.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The term *soccer* comes from Oxford "-er" slang, which was prevalent at the University of Oxford in England from about 1875, and is thought to have been borrowed from the slang of Rugby School.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Initially spelt *assoccer* (a shortening of "association"), it was later reduced to the modern spelling.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Early alternative spellings included *socca* and *socker*.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] This form of slang also gave rise to *rugger* for rugby football, *fiver* and *tenner* for five pound and ten pound notes, and the now-archaic *footer* that was also a name for association football.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] A notable exception is New Zealand, where in the first two decades of the 21st century, under the influence of international television, "football" has been gaining prevalence, despite the dominance of other types of football, namely rugby union and rugby league.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] FIFA has stated that soccer originated in Britain, starting around the eighth century, and that no historical connection exists with any game played in antiquity outside Europe.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The modern rules of association football are based on the mid-19th century efforts to standardise the widely varying forms of football played in the public schools of England.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Kicking ball games arose independently multiple times across multiple cultures.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The Chinese competitive game **cuju** (蹴鞠, literally "kickball"; also known as *tsu chu*) resembles modern association football as well as a mix of basketball and volleyball.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] This is the earliest form of a kicking game for which there is historical evidence.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The game was first recorded as in exercise in the Zhan Guo Ce, a military history from the Han dynasty.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] **Cuju** players would pass the ball around, having to avoid it touching the ground at any point.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] It was then passed to a designated player, who attempted to kick it through the *fengliu yan*, a circular goal atop 10–11 meter poles.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] During the Han dynasty (206 BCE – 220 CE), **cuju** games were standardised and rules were established.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The Silk Road facilitated the transmission of *cuju* outside of China, especially the form of the game popular in the Tang dynasty, the period when the inflatable ball was invented and replaced the stuffed ball.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Other East Asian games include **kemari** in Japan and **chuk-guk** in Korea, both influenced by *cuju*.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] **Kemari** originated after the year 600 during the Asuka period.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] It was a ceremonial rather than a competitive game, and involved the kicking of a *mari*, a ball made of animal skin.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In North America, *pasuckuakohowog* was a ball game played by the Algonquians; it was described as "almost identical to the kind of folk football being played in Europe at the same time, in which the ball was kicked through goals".
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In the Middle Ages, one notable game with similarities to modern football was *calcio storico fiorentino*, which originated in Florence, Italy.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Another medieval sport that can be considered a form of early football is *la soule* (or *choule*), played in France from the 12th century, in which the ball was propelled by hands, feet, and sticks.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] As with pre-codified mob football, the antecedent of all modern football codes, these medieval games involved more handling of the ball than kicking it.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The Cambridge rules, first drawn up at the University of Cambridge in 1848, were particularly influential in the development of subsequent codes, including association football.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The Cambridge rules were written at Trinity College, Cambridge, at a meeting attended by representatives from Eton, Harrow, Rugby, Winchester, and Shrewsbury schools.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] During the 1850s, many clubs unconnected to schools or universities were formed throughout the English-speaking world to play various forms of football.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Some came up with their own distinct codes of rules, most notably the Sheffield Football Club, formed by former public school pupils in 1857, which led to the formation of a Sheffield FA in 1867.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In 1862, John Charles Thring of Uppingham School also devised an influential set of rules.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] These ongoing efforts contributed to the formation of the Football Association (the FA) in 1863, which first met on the morning of 26 October 1863 at the Freemasons' Tavern in Great Queen Street, London.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The only school to be represented on this occasion was Charterhouse.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The Freemasons' Tavern was the setting for five more meetings of the FA between October and December 1863; the English FA eventually issued the first comprehensive set of rules named Laws of the Game, forming modern football.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The laws included bans on running with the ball in hand and hacking (kicking an opponent in the shins), tripping and holding.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Eleven clubs, under the charge of FA secretary Ebenezer Cobb Morley, ratified the original thirteen laws of the game.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The sticking point was hacking, which a twelfth club at the meeting, Blackheath FC, had wanted to keep, resulting in their withdrawal from the FA.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Other English rugby clubs followed this lead and did not join the FA, and instead in 1871, along with Blackheath, formed the Rugby Football Union.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The 1863 FA rules included handling of the ball by "marks" and the lack of a crossbar, making the game remarkably similar to Victorian rules football, which was being developed around the same time in Australia.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The Sheffield FA played by its own rules until the 1870s, with the FA absorbing some of its rules until there was little difference between the games.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The world's oldest football competition is the FA Cup, which was founded by the footballer and cricketer Charles W.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Alcock, and has been contested by English teams since 1872.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The first official international football match also took place in 1872, between Scotland and England in Glasgow, again at the instigation of Alcock.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] England is also home to the world's first football league, which was founded in Birmingham in 1888 by Aston Villa director William McGregor.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The original format contained 12 clubs from the Midlands and Northern England.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The Laws of the Game are determined by the International Football Association Board (IFAB).
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The board was formed in 1886 after a meeting in Manchester of the Football Association, the Scottish Football Association, the Football Association of Wales, and the Irish Football Association.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] FIFA, the international football body, was formed in Paris in 1904 and declared that they would adhere to the Laws of the Game of the Football Association.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The growing popularity of the international game led to the admittance of FIFA representatives to the IFAB in 1913.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The board consists of four representatives from FIFA and one representative from each of the four British associations.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] For most of the 20th century, Europe and South America were the dominant regions in association football.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The FIFA World Cup, inaugurated in 1930, became the main stage for players of both continents to show their worth and the strength of their national teams.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In the second half of the century, the European Cup and the Copa Libertadores were created, and the champions of these two club competitions would contest the Intercontinental Cup to prove which team was the best in the world.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In the 21st century, South America has continued to produce some of the best footballers in the world, but its clubs have fallen behind the still dominant European clubs, which often sign the best players from Latin America and elsewhere.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Meanwhile, football has improved in Africa, Asia, and North America, and nowadays, these regions are at least on equal grounds with South America in club football.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Football is played at a professional level all over the world.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Millions of people regularly go to football stadiums to follow their favourite teams, whilst billions more watch the game on television or on the internet.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] A very large number of people also play football at an amateur level.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] According to a survey conducted by FIFA published in 2001, over 240 million people from more than 200 countries regularly play football.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Football has the highest global television audience in sport.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In many parts of the world, football evokes great passions and plays an important role in the life of individual fans, local communities, and even nations.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Ryszard Kapuściński says that Europeans who are polite, modest, or humble fall easily into rage when playing or watching football games.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] By contrast, football is widely considered to have been the final proximate cause for the Football War in June 1969 between El Salvador and Honduras.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The sport also exacerbated tensions at the beginning of the Croatian War of Independence of the 1990s, when a match between Dinamo Zagreb and Red Star Belgrade degenerated into rioting in May 1990.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The popularity of association football has been connected to identity fusion with replacement fandom collective identities.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Women's association football has historically seen opposition, with national associations severely curbing its development and several outlawing it completely.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Nevertheless, women have been playing football and similar games for as long as such games have existed.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Frescoes from the Han dynasty (25–220 CE) depict female figures playing the ancient Chinese game *cuju*.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] There are also reports of annual football matches played by women in Midlothian, Scotland, during the 1790s.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] There is documented evidence of women's early involvement in association football.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Informal matches between Scotland and England are reported to have taken place in 1881, but are not officially recognised by the respective football associations.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The first women's match recorded by the Scottish Football Association took place in 1892 in Glasgow.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In England, the first recorded game of football between women took place in 1895.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The best-documented early European team was founded by activist Nettie Honeyball in England in 1894: the British Ladies' Football Club.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Honeyball considered women's involvement in football as part of the emancipation movement.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] She and others like her paved the way for women's football.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] However, the women's game was frowned upon by the British football associations and continued without their support.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] It has been suggested that this was motivated by a perceived threat to the "masculinity" of the game.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Women's football became popular on a large scale at the time of the First World War, when female employment in heavy industry spurred the growth of the game, much as it had done for men decades earlier.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The most successful team of the era was Dick, Kerr Ladies F.C. of Preston, England.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] They played in one of the first women's international matches against a French XI team in 1920, and also made up most of the England team against a Scottish Ladies XI in the same year, winning 22–0.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In the early 20th century, women's football in the United Kingdom was mostly associated with charity matches.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Players and football writers have argued that this ban was, in fact, due to envy of the large crowds that women's matches attracted, and because the FA had no control over the money made from the women's game.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The FA ban led to the formation of the short-lived English Ladies Football Association and play moved to rugby grounds.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Women's football also faced bans in several other countries, notably in Brazil from 1941 to 1979, in France from 1941 to 1970, and in West Germany from 1955 to 1970.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In spite of the resistance from governing bodies, British women continued to play football.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Restrictions against female participation in the sport began to be reduced in the late 1960s and the 1970s.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The Italian women's football league was established in 1968.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In December 1969, the Women's Football Association was formed in England, with the sport eventually becoming the most prominent team sport for women in the United Kingdom.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Two unofficial women's World Cups were organised by the FIEFF in 1970 and in 1971.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Also in 1971, UEFA members voted to officially recognise women's football, while the Football Association rescinded the ban that prohibited women from playing on association members' pitches in England.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The first Asian Women's Championship happened in 1975, initially without the approval of the AFC, but later recognised by them.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Women's football still faces many struggles, but its worldwide growth has seen major competitions being launched at both the national and international levels, mirroring the men's competitions.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The FIFA Women's World Cup was inaugurated in 1991: the first tournament was held in China, featuring 12 teams from the six confederations.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The World Cup has been held every four years since; by 2019, it had expanded to 24 national teams, and 1.12 billion viewers watched the competition.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Four years later, FIFA targeted the 32-team 2023 Women's World Cup at an audience of 2 billion, while more than 1.5 million tickets were sold, setting a Women's World Cup record.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Women's football has been an Olympic event since 1996.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] North America is the dominant region in women's football, with the United States winning the most FIFA Women's World Cups and Olympic tournaments.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Europe and Asia come second and third in terms of international success, and the women's game has been improving in South America.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Association football is played in accordance with a set of rules known as the Laws of the Game.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The game is played using a spherical ball of 68–70 cm (27–28 in) circumference, known as the *football* (or *soccer ball*).
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Two teams of eleven players each compete to get the ball into the other team's goal (between the posts and under the bar), thereby scoring a goal.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] There are situations where a goal can be disallowed, such as an offside call or a foul in the build-up to the goal.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The team that has scored more goals at the end of the game is the winner; if both teams have scored an equal number of goals then the game is a draw.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Each team is led by a captain who has only one official responsibility as mandated by the Laws of the Game: to represent their team in the coin toss before kick-off or penalty kicks.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The primary law is that players other than goalkeepers may not deliberately handle the ball with their hands or arms during play, though they must use both their hands during a throw-in restart.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Although players usually use their feet to move the ball around, they may use any part of their body (notably, "heading" with the forehead) other than their hands or arms.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Within normal play, all players are free to play the ball in any direction and move throughout the pitch, though players may not pass to teammates who are in an offside position.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] During gameplay, players attempt to create goal-scoring opportunities through individual control of the ball, such as by dribbling, passing the ball to a teammate, and by taking shots at the goal, which is guarded by the opposing goalkeeper.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Opposing players may try to regain control of the ball by intercepting a pass or through tackling the opponent in possession of the ball; however, physical contact between opponents is restricted.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Football is generally a free-flowing game, with play stopping only when the ball has left the field of play or when play is stopped by the referee for an infringement of the rules.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] After a stoppage, play recommences with a specified restart.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] At a professional level, most matches produce only a few goals.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] For example, the 2022–23 season of the English Premier League produced an average of 2.85 goals per match.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The Laws of the Game do not specify any player positions other than goalkeeper, but a number of specialised roles have evolved.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Broadly, these include three main categories: strikers, or forwards, whose main task is to score goals; defenders, who specialise in preventing their opponents from scoring; and midfielders, who dispossess the opposition and keep possession of the ball to pass it to the forwards on their team.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Players in these positions are referred to as outfield players, to distinguish them from the goalkeeper.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] These positions are further subdivided according to the area of the field in which the player spends the most time.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] For example, there are central defenders and left and right midfielders.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The ten outfield players may be arranged in any combination.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The number of players in each position determines the style of the team's play; more forwards and fewer defenders creates a more aggressive and offensive-minded game, while the reverse creates a slower, more defensive style of play.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] While players typically spend most of the game in a specific position, there are few restrictions on player movement, and players can switch positions at any time.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The layout of a team's players is known as a *formation*.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Defining the team's formation and tactics is usually the prerogative of the team's manager.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] There are seventeen laws in the official Laws of the Game, each containing a collection of stipulations and guidelines.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The same laws are designed to apply to all levels of football for both sexes, although certain modifications for groups such as juniors, seniors and people with physical disabilities are permitted.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The laws are often framed in broad terms, which allow flexibility in their application depending on the nature of the game.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The Laws of the Game are published by FIFA, but are maintained by the IFAB.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In addition to the seventeen laws, numerous IFAB decisions and other directives contribute to the regulation of association football.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Within the United States, Major League Soccer used a distinct ruleset during the 1990s, and the NFHS and NCAA still use rulesets that are comparable to, but different from, the IFAB Laws.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Each team consists of a maximum of eleven players (excluding substitutes), one of whom must be the goalkeeper.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Competition rules may state a minimum number of players required to constitute a team, which is usually seven.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Goalkeepers are the only players allowed to play the ball with their hands or arms, provided they do so within the penalty area in front of their own goal.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Though there are a variety of positions in which the outfield (non-goalkeeper) players are strategically placed by a coach, these positions are not defined or required by the Laws.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The basic equipment or *kit* players are required to wear includes a shirt, shorts, socks, footwear and adequate shin guards.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Wearing an athletic supporter with protective cup is recommended for male players by medical experts and professionals.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Headgear is not a required piece of equipment, but players may choose to wear it to protect themselves from head injury.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Players are forbidden to wear or use anything that is dangerous to themselves or another player, such as jewellery or watches.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The goalkeeper must wear clothing that is easily distinguishable from that worn by the other players and the match officials.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] A number of players may be replaced by substitutes during the course of the game.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The maximum number of substitutions permitted in most competitive international and domestic league games is five in 90 minutes, with each team being allowed one more if the game should go into extra-time; the permitted number may vary in other competitions or in friendly matches.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Common reasons for a substitution include injury, tiredness, ineffectiveness, a tactical switch, or timewasting at the end of a finely poised game.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In standard adult matches, a player who has been substituted may not take further part in a match.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] IFAB recommends "that a match should not continue if there are fewer than seven players in either team".
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Any decision regarding points awarded for abandoned games is left to the individual football associations.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] A game is officiated by a referee, who has "full authority to enforce the Laws of the Game in connection with the match to which he has been appointed" (Law 5), and whose decisions are final.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The referee is assisted by two assistant referees.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In many high-level games there is also a fourth official who assists the referee and may replace another official should the need arise.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Goal line technology is used to measure if the whole ball has crossed the goal-line thereby determining whether a goal has been scored or not; this was brought in to prevent controversy.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Video assistant referees (VAR) have also been increasingly introduced in high-level matches to assist officials through video replays to correct clear and obvious mistakes.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] There are four types of calls that can be reviewed: mistaken identity in awarding a red or yellow card, goals and whether there was a violation during the build-up, direct red card decisions, and penalty decisions.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The ball is spherical with a circumference of between 68 and 70 cm (27 and 28 in), a weight in the range of 410 to 450 g (14 to 16 oz), and a pressure between 0.6 and 1.1 standard atmospheres (8.5 and 15.6 pounds per square inch) at sea level.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In the past the ball was made up of leather panels sewn together, with a latex bladder for pressurisation, but modern balls at all levels of the game are now synthetic.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] As the Laws were formulated in England, and were initially administered solely by the four British football associations within IFAB, the standard dimensions of a football pitch were originally expressed in imperial units.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The Laws now express dimensions with approximate metric equivalents (followed by traditional units in brackets), though use of imperial units remains popular in English-speaking countries with a relatively recent history of metrication (or only partial metrication), such as Britain.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The length of the pitch, or field, for international adult matches is in the range of 100–110 m (110–120 yd) and the width is in the range of 64–75 m (70–80 yd).
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Fields for non-international matches may be 90–120 m (100–130 yd) in length and 45–90 m (50–100 yd) in width, provided the pitch does not become square.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In 2008, the IFAB initially approved a fixed size of 105 m (115 yd) long and 68 m (74 yd) wide as a standard pitch dimension for international matches; however, this decision was later put on hold and was never actually implemented.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The longer boundary lines are *touchlines*, while the shorter boundaries (on which the goals are placed) are *goal lines*.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] A rectangular goal is positioned on each goal line, midway between the two touchlines.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The inner edges of the vertical goal posts must be 7.32 m (24 ft) apart, and the lower edge of the horizontal crossbar supported by the goal posts must be 2.44 m (8 ft) above the ground.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Nets are usually placed behind the goal, but are not required by the Laws.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In front of the goal is the penalty area.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] This area is marked by the goal line, two lines starting on the goal line 16.5 m (18 yd) from the goalposts and extending 16.5 m (18 yd) into the pitch perpendicular to the goal line, and a line joining them.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] This area has a number of functions, the most prominent being to mark where the goalkeeper may handle the ball and where a penalty foul by a member of the defending team becomes punishable by a penalty kick.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Other markings define the position of the ball or players at kick-offs, goal kicks, penalty kicks and corner kicks.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] A standard adult football match consists of two halves of 45 minutes each.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Each half runs continuously, meaning that the clock is not stopped when the ball is out of play.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] There is usually a 15-minute half-time break between halves.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The end of the match is known as full-time.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The referee is the official timekeeper for the match, and may make an allowance for time lost through substitutions, injured players requiring attention, or other stoppages.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] This added time is called "additional time" in FIFA documents, but is most commonly referred to as *stoppage time* or *injury time*, while *lost time* can also be used as a synonym.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The duration of stoppage time is at the sole discretion of the referee.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Stoppage time does not fully compensate for the time in which the ball is out of play, and a 90-minute game typically involves about an hour of "effective playing time".
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The referee alone signals the end of the match.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In matches where a fourth official is appointed, towards the end of the half, the referee signals how many minutes of stoppage time they intend to add.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The fourth official then informs the players and spectators by holding up a board showing this number.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The signalled stoppage time may be further extended by the referee.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Added time was introduced because of an incident in 1891 during a match between Stoke and Aston Villa.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Trailing 1–0 with two minutes remaining, Stoke were awarded a penalty kick.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Villa's goalkeeper deliberately kicked the ball far out of play; by the time it was recovered, the clock had run out and the game was over, leaving Stoke unable to attempt the penalty.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The same rule also states that the duration of either half is extended until a penalty kick to be taken or retaken is completed; thus, no game can end with an uncompleted penalty.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Due to the relatively high ambient temperatures in some regions, cooling breaks for the players were introduced.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Breaks could take place at the referee's discretion after the 30th minute of each half if the wet-bulb globe temperature exceeded 32 °C (90 °F); the breaks would last 3 minutes, with this time made up by an extended period of stoppage time at the end of the half.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In league competitions, games may end in a draw.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In knockout competitions where a winner is required, various methods may be employed to break such a deadlock; some competitions may invoke replays.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] A game tied at the end of regulation time may go into extra time, which consists of two further 15-minute periods.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] If the score is still tied after extra time, some competitions allow the use of penalty shoot-outs (previously known in the Laws of the Game as "kicks from the penalty mark") to determine which team will progress to the next stage of the tournament or be the champion.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Goals scored during extra time periods count towards the final score of the game, but kicks from the penalty mark are only used to decide the team that progresses to the next part of the tournament, with goals scored in a penalty shoot-out not making up part of the final score.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In competitions using two-legged matches, each team competes at home once, with an aggregate score from the two matches deciding which team progresses.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Where aggregates are equal, the away goals rule may be used to determine the winners, in which case the winner is the team that scored the most goals in the leg they played away from home.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] If the result is still equal, extra time and potentially a penalty shoot-out are required.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Under the Laws, the two basic states of play during a game are *ball in play* and *ball out of play*.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] From the beginning of each playing period with a kick-off until the end of the playing period, the ball is in play at all times, except when either the ball leaves the field of play, or play is stopped by the referee.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Players are cautioned with a yellow card, and dismissed from the game with a red card.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] A foul occurs when a player commits an offence listed in the Laws of the Game while the ball is in play.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The offences that constitute a foul are listed in Law 12.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Handling the ball deliberately, tripping an opponent, or pushing an opponent, are examples of "penal fouls", punishable by a direct free kick or penalty kick depending on where the offence occurred.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Other fouls are punishable by an indirect free kick.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The referee may punish a player's or substitute's misconduct by a caution (yellow card) or dismissal (red card).
[src:defense-sports/association-football] A second yellow card in the same game leads to a red card, which results in a dismissal.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] A player given a yellow card is said to have been "booked", the referee writing the player's name in their official notebook.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] If a player has been dismissed, no substitute can be brought on in their place and the player may not participate in further play.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Misconduct may occur at any time, and while the offences that constitute misconduct are listed, the definitions are broad.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In particular, the offence of "unsporting behaviour" may be used to deal with most events that violate the spirit of the game, even if they are not listed as specific offences.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] A referee can show a yellow or red card to a player, substitute, substituted player, and to non-players such as managers and support staff.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Rather than stopping play, the referee may allow play to continue if doing so will benefit the team against which an offence has been committed.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] This is known as "playing an advantage".
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The referee may "call back" play and penalise the original offence if the anticipated advantage does not ensue within "a few seconds".
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Even if an offence is not penalised due to advantage being played, the offender may still be sanctioned for misconduct at the next stoppage of play.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The referee's decision in all on-pitch matters is considered final.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The score of a match cannot be altered after the game, even if later evidence shows that decisions (including whether a goal was awarded or not) were incorrect.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Along with the general administration of the sport, football associations and competition organisers also enforce good conduct in wider aspects of the game, dealing with issues such as comments to the press, clubs' financial management, doping, age fraud and match fixing.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Most competitions enforce mandatory suspensions for players who are sent off in a game.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Some on-field incidents, if considered very serious (such as allegations of racial abuse), may result in competitions deciding to impose heavier sanctions than those normally associated with a red card.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Some associations allow for appeals against player suspensions incurred on-field if clubs feel a referee was incorrect or unduly harsh.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Sanctions for such infractions may be levied on individuals or on clubs as a whole.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Penalties may include fines, point deductions (in league competitions) or even expulsion from competitions.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] For example, the English Football League deduct 12 points from any team that enters financial administration.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Among other administrative sanctions are penalties against game forfeiture.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Teams that forfeit a game or are forfeited against are awarded a technical loss or win.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The recognised international governing body of football (and associated games, such as futsal and beach soccer) is FIFA.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The FIFA headquarters are located in Zürich, Switzerland.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] National associations (or national federations) oversee football within individual countries.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] 211 national associations are affiliated both with FIFA and with their respective continental confederations.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Other national associations may be members of continental confederations but otherwise not participate in FIFA competitions.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] While FIFA is responsible for organising international competitions and enforcing most international regulations, the Laws of the Game are set by the IFAB, where each of the four UK associations holds one vote and FIFA collectively holds four votes.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] International competitions in association football principally consist of two varieties: competitions involving representative national teams or those involving clubs based in multiple nations and national leagues.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] *International football*, without qualification, most often refers to the former.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In the case of international club competition, it is the country of origin of the clubs involved, not the nationalities of their players, that renders the competition international in nature.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The major international competition in football and the most prestigious is the World Cup, organised by FIFA.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] This competition has taken place every four years since 1930, with the exception of the 1942 and 1946 tournaments, which were cancelled because of World War II.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] As of 2022, over 200 national teams compete in qualifying tournaments within the scope of continental confederations for a place in the finals.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The finals tournament involved 32 national teams (expanding to 48 teams for the 2026 tournament) competing over a four-week period.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The World Cup is the world's most widely viewed and most followed sporting event, with the 2022 tournament estimated to be watched by 5 billion people, more than 60% of the global population.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The 1958 World Cup saw the emergence of Pelé as a global sporting star, a period that coincided with "the explosive spread of television, which massively amplified his presence everywhere".
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The current champions are Argentina, who won their third title at the 2022 tournament in Qatar.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The FIFA Women's World Cup has been held every four years since 1991.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Under the tournament's current format that was expanded in 2023, national teams vie for 31 slots in a three-year qualification phase, while the host nation's team enters automatically as the 32nd slot.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The current champions are Spain, after winning their first title in the 2023 tournament.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] There has been a football tournament at every Summer Olympic Games since 1900, except at the 1932 games in Los Angeles when FIFA and the International Olympic Committee (IOC) had disagreed over the status of amateur players.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Before the inception of the World Cup, the Olympics (especially during the 1920s) were the most prestigious international event.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Originally, the tournament was for amateurs only.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] As professionalism spread around the world, the gap in quality between the World Cup and the Olympics widened.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The countries that benefited most were the Soviet Bloc countries of Eastern Europe, where top athletes were state-sponsored while retaining their status as amateurs.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Between 1948 and 1980, 23 out of 27 Olympic medals were won by Eastern Europe, with only Sweden (gold in 1948 and bronze in 1952), Denmark (bronze in 1948 and silver in 1960) and Japan (bronze in 1968) breaking their dominance.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] For the 1984 Los Angeles Games, the IOC allowed professional players to compete.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Since 1992, male competitors must be under 23 years old, although since 1996, three players over the age of 23 have been allowed per squad.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] A women's tournament was added in 1996; in contrast to the men's event, full international sides without age restrictions play the women's Olympic tournament.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] After the World Cup, the most important international football competitions are the continental championships, which are organised by each continental confederation and contested between national teams.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] These are the European Championship (UEFA), the Copa América (CONMEBOL), the Africa Cup of Nations (CAF), the Asian Cup (AFC), the Gold Cup (CONCACAF) and the Nations Cup (OFC).
[src:defense-sports/association-football] These competitions are not strictly limited to members of the continental confederations, with guest teams from other continents sometimes invited to compete.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The FIFA Confederations Cup was contested by the winners of all six continental championships, the current FIFA World Cup champions, and the country which was hosting the next World Cup.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] This was generally regarded as a warm-up tournament for the upcoming FIFA World Cup and did not carry the same prestige as the World Cup itself.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The tournament was discontinued following the 2017 edition, with its calendar slot replaced by an expanded FIFA Club World Cup.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The Finalissima was revived in 2022, and is contested between the Copa América and European Championship winners.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The UEFA Nations League and the CONCACAF Nations League were introduced in the late 2010s to replace international friendlies during the two-year cycle between major tournaments.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The most prestigious competitions in club football are the respective continental championships, which are generally contested between national champions, for example, the UEFA Champions League in Europe and the Copa Libertadores in South America.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The winners of each continental competition contest the FIFA Intercontinental Cup, held annually, and the FIFA Club World Cup, held once every four years.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In each country, football clubs are usually federated in associations or leagues that organise official tournaments among themselves, from which the champion of each country and the teams that will participate in international club tournaments emerge.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] There is no single system of competitions, and each national league organises them according to its own traditions.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The governing bodies in each country operate league systems in a domestic season, normally comprising several divisions, in which the teams gain points throughout the season depending on results, usually three points for a win, one for a draw and zero for a defeat.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Teams are put into tables, placed in order according to points accrued.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In the Old World (Africa, Asia and Europe), it is common for each team to play every other team in its league at home and away in each season, in a round-robin tournament.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] At the end of a season, which typically runs from August to May, the top team is declared the champion.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The top few teams may be promoted to a higher division, and one or more of the teams finishing at the bottom are relegated to a lower division.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The teams finishing at the top of a country's league may also be eligible to play in international club competitions in the following season.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Most countries supplement the league system with one or more "cup" competitions organised on a knock-out basis.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] These include the domestic cup, which may be open to all eligible teams in a country's league system—both professional and amateur—and is organised by the national federation.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Some countries' top divisions feature highly-paid star players; in smaller countries, lower divisions, and many women's clubs, players may be part-timers with a second job, or amateurs.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] The top five European leagues – Premier League (England), Bundesliga (Germany), La Liga (Spain), Serie A (Italy), and Ligue 1 (France) – attract most of the world's best players and, during the 2006–07 season, each of these leagues had a total wage cost in excess of €600 million.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] These leagues also generated a combined €17.2 billion in revenue in the 2021–22 season from television contracts, matchday tickets, sponsorships, and other sources.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In the 2022–23 season, clubs in Europe's "big five" leagues had an aggregate wage cost of €13 billion, with each league spending more than €1.8 billion in wages.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] In contrast, the combined revenue of these leagues was €19.6 billion.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Variants of association football have been codified for teams of reduced size, such as five-a-side football; for non-traditional playing environments, including beach soccer, futsal and indoor soccer; and for athletes with disabilities (Paralympic football).
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Street football can be played with only minimal equipment – a basic game can be played on almost any open area of reasonable size with just a ball made from almost any material and items to mark the positions of the goalposts.
[src:defense-sports/association-football] Such informal games can have team sizes that vary from eleven-a-side, can use a limited or modified subset of the official rules, and can be self-officiated by the players.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] The national governed body of the sport is the "Atya Patya Federation of India".
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] The ministry of Youth Affairs and Sports, government of India, lists the federation amongst its list of recognised federation for the year 2013.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] The federation is headquartered in Nagpur.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] The first south Asian Atya patya Championship was held in Bhutan in June, 2013.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] Some of the alternative names for atya-patya are Killithattu/Klithatu (in Tamil Nadu), Kili Thadthu (in Sri Lanka), Wanjh Wati (in Sindh), Gallery, Sur-pati, Lon-pati, Darya-banth, saragari, saramani, tilli, uppinat, uppupatti, choupal pati, panchwati, and chikka.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] A related Bengali game is Dari Bandha/Dariabandha, in which the attacking team is considered to be "stealing salt" by making it up the court and then "taking the salt back" to the start of the court.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] In Southeast Asia, similar games can be found, such as Galah Panjang/Toi/Tui/Belon Acah in Malaysia, Gobak Sodor/Galah Asin in Indonesia, Htote See Toe in Myanmar, and Patintero in the Philippines.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] Due to the history of Dutch colonialism in the region, the game was also played by Dutch children.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] Atya-patya was mentioned in the Natṟiṇai, which was written before 300 AD.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] It was used as combat practice by soldiers in the Chola dynasty.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] The playing field is a rectangular court, with a central lane or "trench" 89 feet and 1 inch (27.15 m) long marked lengthwise down the middle of the court.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] Nine additional trenches, each 23 feet and 1 inch (7.03 m) long, are drawn on the court perpendicular to the central trench and 11 feet (3.4 m) away from each other, from one end of the court to the other.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] The game is played in four innings (turns), with each inning lasting for seven minutes, and the teams alternating attacking and defending roles in each inning.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] Before each inning, the defensive team places one player in each of the trenches.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] A batch of four players on the attacking team, who are referred to as "assailants", line up at one end of the court, in the area in front of the front trench.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] The goal of the assailants is to score by crossing each trench without being eliminated; the total number of points scored in an inning by the attacking team is equal to the number of trenches crossed by their furthest-advancing assailant.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] If an assailant is touched by a defender (and the defender commits no faults, such as stepping out of their trench, or lifting a foot at or immediately after the time of tagging the assailant), then the assailant is "out", and must leave the court.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] The assailant is also out if they step out of the field while failing to keep any part of their body grounded within the field.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] If an assailant crosses all nine trenches, they may say the word "Tond", which compels the defenders to turn around, allowing the assailant to now attempt to re-cross the nine trenches in the opposite direction.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] Atya-patya matches are decided on a best-of-three basis.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] The defender in the front trench is known as a "grenadier" or "sur", and is able to run in either the front trench or the central trench.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] Grenadiers are allowed to commit any fault other than a foot fault or hand fault where part of their body goes outside of their trench.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] Special rules apply when two or more assailants are encircled by a regular defender and a grenadier, which is known as a "ring".
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] The national level Atya Patya tournament for 2013 was held at Bhatkal in Karnataka.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] Represented by 22 states & Union Territories, the event was organized jointly by Karnataka Atya Patya association Davangere and Bhatkal Atya Patya association.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] The president of Puducherry Atya patya Association, Selvan refuted accusations levelled by Anbhagan, Member of Legislative Assembly, Puducherry, that Atya patya certificates were issued to take benefit of quota available to sports persons, in seats at medical colleges.
[src:defense-sports/atya-patya] He stated that the sport was registered in 22 states of India including in Tamil Nadu.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The playing surface, called a bandy field or bandy rink, is a sheet of ice which measures 90–110 metres (300–360 ft) by 45–65 metres (148–213 ft), about the size of a football pitch.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The field is considerably larger than the ice rinks commonly used for ice hockey.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The sport has a common background with association football, ice hockey, shinty, and field hockey.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy's origins are debatable, but its first rules were organized and published in England in 1882.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Internationally, bandy's strongest nations in both men's and women's competitions have long been Sweden and Russia; both countries have established professional men's bandy leagues.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In Russia, it is estimated that more than one million people play bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The sport also has organized league play and fans in other countries, including Finland, Norway, and Kazakhstan.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The premier international bandy competition for men is the Bandy World Championship and for women it is the Women's Bandy World Championship.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Organized bandy started in the late 19th century; however, until 1955, there was no established international governing body for the sport.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The international governing body for bandy today is the Federation of International Bandy (FIB) which formed in February 1955.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In 2001, bandy was recognized as a sport by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Both traditional eleven-a-side bandy and rink bandy (which is played on a smaller rink) are recognized by the IOC.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Based on the number of participating athletes, the FIB has claimed bandy is the world's second-most participated winter sport after ice hockey.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The earliest origin of the sport is debated.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The mid-eighteenth-century *Devonshire Dialogue* collection lists Bandy as "a game, like that of Golf, in which the adverse parties endeavour to beat a ball (generally a knob or gnarl from the trunk of a tree,) opposite ways... the stick with which the game is played is crook'd at the end".
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The sport's first published set of organized rules was codified in 1882 by Charles Goodman Tebbutt of the Bury Fen Bandy Club.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] When the international federation was founded in 1955, it came about after a compromise between Russian and English rules, in which more of the English rules prevailed.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Since association football was already popular in England, the codified bandy rules took after much of the football rules.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Like association football, games are normally two 45 minute halves and there are 11 players per side.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Players sticks are curved like large field hockey sticks and the bandy ball is roughly the size of a tennis ball with a cork core and hard plastic coating.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy balls were originally usually red but are now either orange or more commonly cerise.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy as an ice skating sport first developed in England.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] It developed as a winter sport in the Fens of East Anglia.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Large expanses of ice would form on the flooded meadows or shallow washes in cold winters where fen skating, which has been a tradition dating back to at least medieval times, took place.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy's early recorded modernization period can be traced back to 1813.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Members of the Bury Fen Bandy Club published rules of the game in 1882, and introduced it into other European countries.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A variety of stick and ball games involving ice skating were introduced to North America by the 1800s but failed to organize and develop popular rules codes.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] However, these stick and ball games became one of the eventual antecedents of the modern sport of ice hockey, whose first rules were codified in Canada in 1875.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The first international bandy match took place in 1891 between Bury Fen and the Haarlemsche Hockey & Bandy Club from the Netherlands (a club which after a couple of club fusions now is named HC Bloemendaal).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The same year, the National Bandy Association was established as a governing body for the sport in England.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] National governing federations for bandy were also founded in the 1890s in the Netherlands and Russia and in the following decade in Finland (then part of the Russian Empire), Sweden, and Norway.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The match later dubbed "the original bandy match", was actually held in 1875 at The Crystal Palace in London.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] However, at the time, the game was called "hockey on the ice", probably as it was considered an ice variant of field hockey.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] An early maker of bandy sticks was the firm of Gray's, Cambridge.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] One such stick, now in the collections of the Museum of Cambridge, has a length of rope twisted round the handle to rescue any player who might fall through the ice, as the game was played on frozen lakes back then.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] An 1899 photo of two players demonstrating the game shows the sticks being held single-handed.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Historically, bandy was a popular sport in some central and western European countries until the First World War, and from 1901 to 1926 it was played in the Scandinavian Nordic Games, the first international multi-sport event focused on winter sports.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The first national bandy league in modern history was started in Sweden in 1902.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy was played at the Nordic Games in both Stockholm and Kristiania (present day Oslo) in 1901, 1903, 1905, 1909, 1913, 1917, 1922 and 1926, and between Swedish, Finnish and Russian teams at similar games in Helsinki in 1907.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy appeared as a sport in all eight editions of the Nordic Games from 1901 to 1926.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The Spartakiad was an international multisport event arranged by workers' sports clubs in the 1920s and 1930s and sponsored by the Soviet Union.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In the first Winter Spartakiad, held in Oslo, Norway, in 1928, bandy was played by teams from Norway, the Soviet Union and Sweden.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy was played as a demonstration sport at the 1952 Oslo Olympics.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Finland defeated Norway 3-2 in front of 500 fans.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Norway then took on the Swedes later that day, with 3000 people watching as the underdog Norwegians defeated Sweden 2-1, which was their first recorded victory versus their larger neighbor.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In the final game, Sweden beat Finland 4-0.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The sport's English name comes from the verb "to bandy", from the Middle French *bander* ("to strike back and forth"), and originally referred to a seventeenth-century Irish game similar to field hockey.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The curved stick was also called a "bandy".
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The etymological connection to the similarly named Welsh hockey game of bando is not clear.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] An old name for bandy is *hockey on the ice*; in the first rule books from England at the turn of the century 1900, the sport is literally called "bandy or hockey on the ice".
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Since the early 20th century, the term bandy is usually preferred to prevent confusion with ice hockey.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The sport is known as bandy in many languages, with a few exceptions.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In Russia, bandy is called "Russian hockey" (русский хоккей) or more frequently, and officially, "hockey with a ball" (хоккей с мячом) while ice hockey is called "hockey with a puck" (хоккей с шайбой) or more frequently just "hockey".
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] If the context makes it clear that bandy is the subject, it as well can be called just "hockey".
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In Belarusian, Ukrainian and Bulgarian it is also called "hockey with a ball" (хакей з мячoм, хокей з м'ячем and хокей с топка respectively).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In Slovak "bandy hockey" (*bandyhokej*) is the name.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In Armenian, Kazakh, Kyrgyz, Mongol and Uzbek, bandy is known as "ball hockey" (գնդակով հոկեյ, допты хоккей, топтуу хоккей, бөмбөгтэй хоккей and *koptokli xokkey* respectively).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In Finnish the two sports are distinguished as "ice ball" (*jääpallo*) and "ice puck" (*jääkiekko*), as well as in Hungarian (*jéglabda; jégkorong*), although in Hungarian it is more often called "bandy" nowadays.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In Estonian and Lithuanian bandy is also called "ice ball" (*jääpall*; *ledo riedulys*).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In Mandarin Chinese it is "bandy ball" (班迪球).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In Scottish Gaelic the name is "ice shinty" (*camanachd-deighe*).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In old times shinty or shinney were also sometimes used in English for bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Because of its similarities with association football, bandy is also nicknamed "winter football" (Swedish: *Vinterns fotboll*).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] It is natural that bandy got the nickname 'winter football'.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] It was common for sports clubs to have both a bandy and a football section, with athletes playing both sports but at different times of the year.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Some examples are *Nottingham Forest Football and Bandy Club* in England (today known just as Nottingham Forest F.C.) and Norwegian Strømsgodset IF and Mjøndalen IF, with both having an active bandy section.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In Sweden, most football clubs that were active during the first half of the 20th century also played bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Swedish player Orvar Bergmark earned silver medals in the world championships of both sports in the 1950s.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Later, as the season for each sport increased in time, it was not as easy for the players to engage in both sports, so some clubs came to concentrate on one or the other.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Many old clubs still have both sports on their program.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Sten-Ove Ramberg is the last Swedish male player in both national teams (1978 in bandy, 1979–1984 in football).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] No clear distinction between bandy and ice hockey was made before the 1920s.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] As bandy in a way can be seen as a precursor to ice hockey, bandy has influenced the development and history of ice hockey, mainly in European and former Soviet countries.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] While modern ice hockey was created in Canada, a variety of games which bore a closer resemblance to bandy were initially played there after British soldiers introduced the game of bandy in the late 19th century.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] At the same time as modern ice hockey rules were formalized in British North America (present-day Canada), bandy rules were decided upon in Europe.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Before Canadians introduced ice hockey into Europe in the early 20th century, "hockey" was another name for bandy, and still is in parts of Russia and Kazakhstan.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Both bandy and ice hockey were played in Europe during the 20th century, especially in Sweden, Finland, and Norway.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Ice hockey became more popular than bandy in most of Europe, mostly because it had become an Olympic sport, while bandy had not.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Athletes in Europe who had played bandy switched to ice hockey in the 1920s to compete in the Olympics.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The smaller ice fields needed for ice hockey also made its rinks easier to maintain, especially in countries with short winters.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] On the other hand, ice hockey was not played in the Soviet Union until the 1950s, when the USSR wanted to compete internationally.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The typical European style of ice hockey, with flowing, less physical play, represents a heritage of bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Since the 1950s, when the Soviet Union ended its isolation and started to take part in international sports events, there has been a reason to play world championships.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The International Bandy Federation was founded in 1955 and the first world championships were played in 1957 with the Soviet Union and then Russia (as its successor country in 1993) almost consistently in a top position in the sport of bandy alongside Sweden.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In a similar fashion, Russia, along with Sweden, has emerged as one of the two dominant women's bandy nations internationally in the Women's Bandy World Championship.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Women's bandy uses the exact same rules as men, but the women's game is played separately.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Women have been playing bandy since the sport was originally developed.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Although there were several attempts in the early part of the 19th century to organize bandy leagues for women's teams, regular leagues only started in the 1970s in Sweden and Finland and then later in the 1980s in Norway and the Soviet Union.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The highest altitude where bandy has been played is in Khorugh, the capital of the Tajik autonomous province of Gorno-Badakhshan.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Khorugh is situated 2,200 metres (7,200 feet) above sea level in the Pamir Mountains.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Starting in the 1980s and increasingly since the turn of the millennium, more and more indoor arenas for bandy have been built (often as joint arenas to be used also for football or speed skating).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The use of indoor arenas makes the effects of the weather on a game virtually insignificant, something which earlier always have been a factor to consider for the teams and the audiences.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] However, unlike some other sports, bandy is still the same game with the same rules indoors or outdoors and no changes are made to the rules depending on whether there's a roof overhead or not.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Many games, even in the highest leagues, are still played outdoors.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In Sweden there are more indoor arenas than in all other countries combined.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy is played on ice, using a single round bandy ball.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Two teams of 11 players each compete to get the ball into the other team's goal using bandy sticks, thereby scoring a goal.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The team that has scored more goals at the end of the game is the winner.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] If both teams have scored an equal number of goals, then, with some exceptions, the game is a draw.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The game is designed to be played on a rectangular sheet of ice, called a bandy field, which is the same size as a football (soccer) field.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In a typical game, players attempt to propel the ball toward their opponents' goal through individual control of the ball, such as by dribbling, passing the ball to a teammate, and taking shots at the goal, which is guarded by the opposing goalkeeper.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Opposing players may try to regain control of the ball by intercepting a pass or tackling the opponent who controls the ball.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] However, physical contact between opponents is limited.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy is generally a free-flowing game, with play stopping only when the ball has left the field of play, or when play is stopped by the referee.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] After a stoppage, play can recommence with a free stroke, a penalty shot or a corner stroke.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] If the ball has left the field along the sidelines, the referee must decide which team touched the ball last, and award a restart stroke to the opposing team, just like football's throw-in.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In terms of rules, bandy has several rules that are similar to football.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Each team has 11 players, one of whom is a goalkeeper.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Goalkeepers use gloves made specifically for their position and wear them on both hands but do not use any type of stick.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The offside rule, which in general is similar to the one used in football, is also employed.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A goal cannot be scored from a goal throw, but unlike football, a goal can be scored from a stroke-in.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] All free strokes are "direct" and allow a goal to be scored without another player touching the ball.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A primary rule is that players (other than the goalkeepers) may not intentionally touch the ball with their heads, hands or arms during play.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Although players usually use their sticks to move the ball around, they may use any part of their bodies other than their heads, hands or arms and may use their skates in a limited manner.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The rules do not specify any player positions other than goalkeeper, but a number of player specialisations have evolved.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Players in these positions are referred to as outfield players, to discern them from the single goalkeeper.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] These positions are further differentiated by which side of the field the player spends most time in.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] For example, there are central defenders, and left and right midfielders.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] While players may spend most of the game in a specific position, there are few restrictions on player movement, and players can switch positions at any time.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The layout of the players on the pitch is called the team's formation, and defining the team's formation and tactics is usually the prerogative of the team's manager(s).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Formation in bandy is often comparable to the formation in association football.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Shouldering is allowed in checking situations and body contact therefore does occur, but body checking and fighting are illegal.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Elite players have a mean skating velocity of over 16 km/h (10 mph) and the skating velocity can in some cases reach 37 km/h (23 mph).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] There are eighteen rules in official play, designed to apply to all levels of bandy, although certain modifications for groups such as juniors, veterans or women are permitted.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The rules are often framed in broad terms, which allow flexibility in their application depending on the nature of the game.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A game is officiated by a referee, the authority and enforcer of the rules, whose decisions are final.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The referee may have one or two assistant referees.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A secretary outside of the field often takes care of the match protocol.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The Bandy Playing Rules can be found on the official website of the Federation of International Bandy, and are overseen by the Rules and Referee Committee.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Each team consists of a maximum of 11 players (excluding substitutes), one of whom must be the goalkeeper.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A team of fewer than eight players may not start a game.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Goalkeepers are the only players allowed to play the ball with their hands or arms, and they are only allowed to do so within the penalty area in front of their own goal.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Though there are a variety of positions in which the outfield (non-goalkeeper) players are strategically placed by a coach, these positions are not defined or required by the rules of the game.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The positions and formations of the players in bandy are virtually the same as the common association football positions and the same terms are used for the different positions of the players.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A team usually consists of defenders, midfielders and forwards.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The defenders can play in the form of centre-backs, full-backs and sometimes wing-backs, midfielders playing in the centre, attacking or defensive, and forwards in the form of centre forward, second strikers and sometimes a winger.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Sometimes one player is also taking up the role of a libero.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Any number of players may be replaced by substitutes during the course of the game.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Substitutions can be performed without notifying the referee and can be performed while the ball is in play.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] However, the substitute must leave the ice before the teammate enters it.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A team can bring at the most four substitutes to the game, five if one of these is an extra goalkeeper.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Formation in bandy describes how the players in a team generally position themselves on the rink and is often comparable to the formation in association football.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The team's manager(s) define the team's formation while tactics are usually their prerogative as well.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy is a fluid and fast-moving game, and (with the exception of the goalkeeper) a player's position in a formation defines their role less rigidly than — for instance — for a rugby player, nor are there episodes in play where players must expressly line up in formation (as in gridiron football).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The bandy games are more similar to association football in this regard.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Nevertheless, a player's position in a formation generally defines whether a player has a mostly defensive or attacking role, and whether they tend to play towards one side of the pitch or centrally.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A standard adult bandy match consists of two periods of 45 minutes each, known as halves.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Each half runs continuously, meaning the clock is not stopped when the ball is out of play; the referee can, however, make allowance for time lost through significant stoppages as described below.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] There is usually a 15-minute half-time break.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The referee is the official timekeeper for the match and may make an allowance for time lost through substitutions, injured players requiring attention, or other stoppages.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] This added time is commonly referred to as *stoppage time* or *injury-time*, and must be reported to the match secretary and the two captains.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] If it is very cold or if it is snowing, the match can be broken into thirds of 30 minutes each.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] At the extremely cold 1999 World Championship some matches were played in four periods of 15 minutes each and with extra long breaks in between.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In the World Championships the two halves can be 30 minutes each for the nations in the B division.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In league competitions, games may end in a draw, but in some knockout competitions if a game is tied at the end of regulation time it may go into extra time, which usually consists of two further 10-minute periods.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] If the score is still tied after extra time, the game will be decided on penalties.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The teams shoot five penalties each and if this doesn't settle the game, the teams shoot one more penalty each until one of them misses and the other scores.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Under the rules, the two basic states of play during a game are *ball in play* and *ball out of play*.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] From the beginning of each playing period with a stroke-off (a set strike from the centre-spot by one team) until the end of the playing period, the ball is in play at all times, except when either the ball leaves the field of play, or play is stopped by the referee.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] If the time runs out while a team is preparing for a free-stroke or penalty, the strike should still be made but it must go into the goal by one shot to count as a goal.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Similarly, a goal made via a corner stroke should be allowed, but it must be executed using only one shot in addition to the strike needed to put the ball in play.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Free-strokes can be awarded to a team if a player of the opposite team breaks any rule, for example, by hitting with the stick against the opponent's stick or skates.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Free-strokes can also be awarded upon incorrect execution of corner-strikes, free-strikes, goal-throws, and so on, or the use of incorrect equipment, such as a broken stick.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Rather than stopping play, the referee may allow play to continue when its continuation will benefit the team against which an offence has been committed.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The referee may "call back" play and penalise the original offence if the anticipated advantage does not ensue within a short period of time, typically taken to be four to five seconds.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Even if an offence is not penalised because the referee plays an advantage, the offender may still be sanctioned (see below) for any associated misconduct at the next stoppage of play.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] If a defender violently attacks an opponent within the penalty area, a penalty shot is awarded.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Certain other offences, when carried out within the penalty area, for instance a defender holding or hooking an attacker, or blocking a goal situation with a lifted skate, thrown stick or glove and so on result in a penalty shot.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Also, the defenders (with the exception of the goal-keeper) are not allowed to kneel or lie on the ice.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The final offences that might mandate a penalty shot are those of hitting or blocking an opponent's stick or touching the ball with the hands, arms, stick or head.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A 10-minute penalty or a red card may be issued to the offending player as well.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A yellow card indicates a warning given to an entire team for technical fouls such as errors in the execution of goal-throws or free strokes, or the obstruction of a player without ball.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Subsequent technical fouls by the same team result in a five-minute penalty indicated by a white card.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A five-minute penalty is traditionally indicated using a white card but today the card is rarely shown, rather an announcement from the match secretary or the referee is used instead.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In a similar manner, traditionally a ten-minute penalty is indicated by use of a blue card.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A ten-minute penalty can be given for protesting or behaving incorrectly, attacking an opponent violently or stopping the ball incorrectly to get an advantage.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The third time a player receives a time penalty, it will be a personal penalty, meaning he or she will miss the remainder of the match.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A substitute can enter the field after five or ten minutes, depending on the type of time penalty received.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A full game penalty can be received upon using abusive language or directly attacking an opponent and means that the player can neither play nor be substituted for the remainder of the game.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A match penalty is indicated through the use of a red card.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The offside rule effectively limits the ability to attack players to remain forward (i.e. closer to the opponent's goal-line) of the ball, the second-to-last defending player (which can include the goalkeeper), and the half-way line.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] This rule is in general similar to that of soccer.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The basic equipment players are required to wear includes a pair of bandy skates, a helmet, a mouthguard and, in the case of the goalkeeper, a faceguard.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The teams must wear uniforms that make it easy to distinguish the two teams.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The goalkeeper wears distinct colours to be singled out from his or her teammates, just as in football.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The ice skates, sticks and any tape on the stick must be of another colour than the bandy ball, which is orange or cerise.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In addition to the aforementioned items, various pieces of gear are used to protect the knees, elbows, genitals and throat.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The pants and gloves may contain padding.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The core of the ball is made of cork and is surrounded by rubber or rubber-like plastic.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Balls should be manufactured in a diameter of 62.4 or 63.8 mm (2.46 or 2.51 in) (the latter is called a "Russian ball").
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Originally, bandy balls were red, then later became orange or cerise.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] According to the Bandy Playing Rules set up by the Federation of International Bandy, any of these are allowed, but all balls used in one game must be of the same colour and type.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The stick used in bandy is an essential part of the sport.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] It should be made of an approved material such as wood or a similar material and should not contain any metal or sharp parts which can hurt the surrounding players.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Sticks are crooked and are available in five angles, where 1 has the smallest bend and 5 has the most.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bend 4 is the most common size in professional bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The bandy stick should not have similar colours to the ball, such as orange or pink; it should be no longer than 127 centimetres (50 in), and no wider than 7 centimetres (2.8 in).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A bandy field is 45–65 metres (148–213 ft) by 90–110 metres (300–360 ft), a total of 4,050–7,150 square metres (43,600–77,000 sq ft), or about the same size as a football pitch and considerably larger than an ice hockey rink, which is 25–30 metres (82–98 ft) by 60 metres (200 ft).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Along the sidelines a 15 cm (6 in) high border (vant, sarg, wand, wall) is placed to prevent the ball from leaving the ice.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] It should not be attached to the ice, to glide upon collisions, and should end 1–3 metres (3 ft 3 in – 9 ft 10 in) away from the corners.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Centered at each shortline is a 3.5 m (11 ft) wide and 2.1 m (6 ft 11 in) high goal cage and in front of the cage is a half-circular penalty area with a 17 m (56 ft) radius.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A penalty spot is located 12 metres (39 ft) in front of the goal and there are two free-stroke spots at the penalty area line, each surrounded by a 5 m (16 ft) circle.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A centre spot with a circle of radius 5 m (16 ft) denotes the center of the field.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] A centre-line is drawn through the centre spot parallel with the shortlines.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] At each of the corners, a 1 m (3 ft 3 in) radius quarter-circle is drawn, and a dotted line is painted parallel to the shortline and 5 metres (16 ft) away from it without extending into the penalty area.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The dotted line can be replaced with a 0.5-metre (1 ft 8 in) long line starting at the edge of the penalty area and extending towards the sideline, 5 metres (16 ft) from the shortline.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The goal cage used in bandy is3.5 m (11 ft) wide and 2.1 metres (6 feet 11 inches) high and is the largest one used by any organized winter team sport.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy players require protective equipment, some of which is designed specifically for the sport such as the bandy chinguard.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Equipment is similar to that worn in ice hockey but is typically smaller, lighter, and more flexible, and more closely resembles the equipment worn in the modern sport of ringette.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] All players are required to wear helmets.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] While some bandy players are required to wear facemasks such as young players, some outfield players only wear a helmet with a bandy chin guard.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Goaltenders are the exception and must wear a helmet and facemask at all times.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The first international games were played by club teams in the 1890s.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Starting in the first decade of the 20th century, friendlies were played between national teams of some European countries.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] While games like this did not take place in central and western Europe after the 1910s, the Nordic countries of Estonia, Finland, Norway, and Sweden continued, doing it more regularly during the 1920s and 1930s with annually or semi-annually recurring friendlies between some of them.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Sweden tried to arrange for friendly games against the Soviet Union in the latter half of the 1940s, but it did not come to be until the mid-1950s.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy was played as one of the sports at the Nordic Games, international winter sports events held during the first few decades of the 20th century.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The Fédération internationale de hockey sur glace, or International Ice Hockey Federation as it is more well known as today, was founded in 1908 and was governing some bandy competitions in its early years, before only concentrating on ice hockey.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The Federation of International Bandy (FIB) was formed as *International Bandy Federation* in 1955 and has had 33 members at most, each representing a country where bandy is played.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Currently, there are 27 members of the federation.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The name of the federation was changed to the present one in 2001 after the International Olympic Committee approved it as a so-called "recognized sport".
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The abbreviation "IBF" was at the time already used by another recognized sports federation, and IOC considers it important that the official abbreviations of sports federations are unique, so that the federations are not mistaken for one another.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] FIB is now a member of Association of IOC Recognised International Sports Federations.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The Bandy World Championship for men is arranged by the FIB and was first held in 1957.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] It was held every two years starting in 1961, and every year since 2003.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Currently, the record number of countries participating in the World Championships is twenty (2019).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Since the number of countries playing bandy is not large, every country which can set up a team is welcome to take part in the World Championship.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The quality of the teams varies; however, with only six nations, Sweden, the Soviet Union, Russia, Finland, Norway, and Kazakhstan, having won medals (allowing for the fact that Russia's team took over from the Soviet Union in 1993).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Finland won the 2004 world championship in Västerås, Sweden, while all other championships have been won by Sweden, the Soviet Union and Russia.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The Soviet Union won all championships until 1981, when Sweden managed to break the streak of eleven straight gold medals.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Sweden won again in the next tournament in 1983, but Soviet again seized the victory in 1985.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The Soviet Union also won at its last two appearances, and then Sweden won in 1993, 1995 and 1997.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Russia, having taken over after the Soviet Union, and Sweden have kept on winning all championships between them except for 2004, when Finland managed to claim the win.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In 2020, the B division of the World Championship was played, but the A division – which was to be played about a month later – was first postponed a couple of times due to the outbreak of the COVID-19 pandemic and later moved to the next year as the pandemic did not end.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The championship tournament could however not be played in 2021 either.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The first World Championship for women took place in February 2004 in Lappeenranta, Finland.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Sweden won the championship without conceding a goal.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In the 2014 women's World Championship Russia won for the first time, defeating Sweden, making it the first time Sweden did not win the world title.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The 2018 women's tournament was played in a country situated completely in Asia for the first time, when it was hosted in Chengde, China.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] It was the same for the men's tournament that same year (the area north and west of the Ural River is located in Europe, thus Kazakhstan, which had hosted a world championship before, is a transcontinental country), when Harbin hosted the 2018 Division B tournament.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The 2020 championship saw China withdraw its participation due to the COVID-19 pandemic, but the tournament was held in Norway in February and the pandemic had not yet reached Europe.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In 2022 when the championship was played in Sweden, China did not yet return, while Russia and Ukraine both withdrew because of the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] There are also Youth Bandy World Championships in different age groups for boys and young men and in one age group for girls.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The oldest group is the under 23 championship, Bandy World Championship Y-23.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] During most of the 20th century, a host nation for Olympic Games had the right to arrange demonstration games for almost any sport of its own choosing.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In 1952, the Winter Olympic Games were arranged in Oslo, Norway, and the Norwegians presented bandy as a demonstration sport.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The tournament of bandy at the 1952 Winter Olympics was played by three countries, Norway, Finland and Sweden.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] This is the only time bandy has been played at Olympic Games.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy was officially recognized by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) under the Association of IOC Recognised International Sports Federations (ARISF) in 2004, and was played as a demonstration sport at the 1952 Winter Olympics in Oslo.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] However, it has yet to officially be played at the Olympics.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] According to the FIB, bandy is the world's second-most participated winter sport after ice hockey based on the number of participating athletes.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] It is unclear how many of the players participate in the male category and how many in the female category.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The FIB has also recorded bandy (men's) as having ranked as the number two winter sport in terms of tickets sold per day of competitions at the sport's world championship.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] However, compared with the seven Winter Olympic sports, bandy's popularity among other winter sports across the globe is considered by the International Olympic Committee to have a, "gap between popularity and participation and global audiences", which is a roadblock to future Olympic inclusion.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In addition, the Olympic Charter requires a sport to be widely practiced by men in at least 75 countries and on four continents, and by women in no fewer than 40 countries and on three continents in order to be accepted.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] FIB president Boris Skrynnik lobbied for bandy to be included in the 2014 Winter Olympics in Sochi, given Russia's prominence in the sport.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Members of the Chinese Olympic Committee were present at the 2017 world championships to meet with Skrynnik about the possibility of considering the sport for the 2022 Winter Olympics in Beijing.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] However, in 2018 it was announced no new sports would be added for 2022.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] At the 2011 Asian Winter Games, open to members of the Olympic Council of Asia, men's bandy was included for the first time.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Three teams contested the inaugural competition, and Kazakhstan won the gold medal.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The President of Kazakhstan, Nursultan Nazarbayev, attended the final.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] There was no bandy competition at the next Games, the 2017 Asian Winter Games held in Japan.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Bandy made its debut at the Winter Universiade during the 2019 Games in Krasonyarsk, Russia.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Originally a six-team tournament for men and a four-team tournament for women were planned to be held.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] However, later China withdrew from the men's tournament and was supposed to be replaced by Belarus.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Since that did not happen either, participating teams among women were Russia, Sweden, Norway and the United States, while among men Russia, Sweden, Norway, Finland and Kazakhstan.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The World Championships should not be confused with the annual Bandy World Cup competitions.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The Bandy World Cup for men in Ljusdal, Sweden, has been played annually since the 1970s and is the biggest bandy tournament for elite-level club teams.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] It is played indoors in Sandviken since 2009 because Ljusdal has no indoor arena.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] It is expected to return to Ljusdal once an indoor arena has been built.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] World Cup matches are played day and night, and the tournament is played in four days in late October.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The teams participating are mostly, and some years exclusively, from Sweden and Russia, which has the two best leagues in the world.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic led to the Cup being cancelled in 2020 and 2021.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] There is also a club competition for women's bandy teams called Bandy World Cup Women.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The European Cup was first played in 1974 and was a competition featuring the national men's champion team from any European country which had a national bandy championship.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] This meant, at the time, that only four teams competed every year, which were the men's champions from Finland, Norway, the Soviet Union, and Sweden.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] After the Soviet Union had been dissolved in 1991, the Russian champions took part instead.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The cup is not formally defunct, but the last installment was played in 2009.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The Federation of International Bandy usually arranges a four nations tournament every year between national teams from Norway, Finland, Russia and Sweden.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The 2022 tournament was originally set for 21–23 January, but was cancelled after the Swedish Bandy Association announced they would not be hosting it for that season.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] During the period 1972–1990, the Rossiya Tournament was held semi-annually for national teams in the years when there was no world championship.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] This tournament was always played in the Soviet Union and arranged by the newspaper *Sovetskaya Rossiya*.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] It was affectionately called "the small world championship".
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] From 1992 the tournament was renamed Russian Government Cup.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] There has likely never been any European Championship played in bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Some sources describe a 1913 European Bandy Championships as having been held in February 1913, in Switzerland, at the same time as the bandy tournament at the 1913 Nordic Games.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] However, this European Championship tournament likely never happened, or is a conflation of titles, since no contemporary sources have been found.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] There are several existing international bandy competitions with events varying based upon age, competitive level, and sex.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Varieties of bandy exist, utilising the same rules only with slight differences, like seven-a-side bandy with regulation sized goal cages but without corner strokes and often on a smaller sized rink.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Seven-a-side bandy was popular in central Europe and in England in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, while eleven-a-side bandy was preferred in the Nordic countries and in Russia.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Seven-a-side bandy rules were applied at the Davos Cup in 2016.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Rink bandy is a bandy variant played on an ice hockey-size rink.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] It was originally conceived as a way of practicing bandy in the summertime, when there were no bandy sized indoor rinks but ice hockey rinks had started to be built indoors.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Rink bandy is played by basically the same rules as regular bandy but on a playing surface the size of an ice hockey rink with ice hockey goal cages and six players on each team (or five in the case of the USA Rink Bandy League).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] There have been international competitions for rink bandy played by the best bandy players in the 1980s and 1990s, both for club teams and for national teams, there were world championships in rink bandy in those days and the Hofors World Cup for clubs was played annually from 1984 to 1998.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] When more indoor bandy rinks have been built, rink bandy has more become a sport for lower league teams and recreational play.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Rink bandy was played in the 2012 European Company Sports Games program.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In Czechia, the national federation has developed its own version of rink bandy with somewhat different rules, which is meant to help the players transition to playing on a full-sized bandy rink.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Read more in the section on Czechia below.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] Rink bandy has in turn led to the creation of the sport of rinkball.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The sport of rinkball has at times been referred to as a variant of bandy, however it organized by the 1980s and has since become an established organized sport with its own governing body and differs considerably from both bandy and ice hockey, the sport's two major influences.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] In Sweden, informal games played like bandy but on ice-free ground (usually on gravel or asphalt concrete) are called *landbandy*.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] The term should not be confused with *landhockey*, the Swedish term for field hockey.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] There is no formal roller sport companion to bandy involving either inline skates or parallel wheel roller skates, even if rink hockey can be considered to have some similarities with bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p01] There is also no formally organized skateless ice variant of bandy, and bandy does not have any parasport variant.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy has been played in Canada since the 1980s, but is not nearly as popular as ice hockey in this country.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Friendlies are played against the United States.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Canadian bandy federation is called Canada Bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The China Bandy Federation was set up in 2014.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Since them, China has since participated in a number of world championship tournaments, with men's, women's and youth teams.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] China Bandy is mainly financed by private resources.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The development of the sport in China is supported by the Harbin Sport University.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] A team from Prague in present-day Czechia became Austrian national bandy champions in 1911.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Czechia has been playing in the World Championship since 2016.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] As a way of preparing as well as possible for international matches, the Czechs have invented modified rules for games on ice hockey rinks, a variety called short bandy, which differs from rink bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Czech (former rink bandy) national league is now called *Liga českého národního bandy*.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy as an organized sport was played in Estonia in the 1910s to 1930s and the country had a national championship for some years.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The national team played friendlies against Finland in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The sport was played sporadically during the Soviet occupation 1944–1991.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] It has since then become more organized again, partly through exchange with Finnish clubs and enthusiasts.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] As of 2018, Estonia takes part in both the Bandy World Championship for men, and the Women's Bandy World Championship.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy as an organized sport was introduced to Finland from Russia in the 1890s.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Finland has been playing bandy friendlies against Sweden and Estonia since its independence in 1917.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The first men's Finnish national championships were held in 1908 and was the first national Finnish championship held in any team sport.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] National champions have been named every year except for three years in the first half of the 20th century when Finland was at war.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The top national league is called Bandyliiga and is semi-professional.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The best players turn fully professional by being recruited by clubs in Sweden or Russia.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] As of the 2020–21 season, Bandyliiga consisted of the following teams: Akilles, Botnia-69, HIFK, JPS, Kampparit, Narukerä, OLS, Veiterä and WP 35.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Finland was an original member of the Federation of International Bandy and is the only country besides Russia/Soviet Union and Sweden to have won a Bandy World Championship, which it did in 2004.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Federation of International Bandy (FIB) is planning for a major premiere for indoor bandy in Finland in 2023 with the venue taking place at an indoor arena in Lappeenranta.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] When the arena is ready, an international inauguration is to take place with a 4-nation bandy tournament.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Participants will include teams from Russia, Sweden, Norway and Finland.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The tournament is scheduled for 20–22 January 2023.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy was played in Germany in the early 20th century, including by Crown Prince Wilhelm, but the interest died out in favour of ice hockey.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Leipziger Sportclub, which arguably had the best team, was also the last club to give bandy up.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The sport was reintroduced to Germany in the 2010s, with the German Bandy Federation being founded in 2013.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Germany has been participating in the Bandy World Championship, a competition for male competitors, since 2014.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy is being played in northern parts of India close to the Himalayas, where there is usually cold weather and snow in the winter time.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] A national championship is contested every year, but India has yet to send a national team to the World Championships or any other international competition.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy has a long history in many parts of Kazakhstan and it used to be one of the most popular sports in Soviet times.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] However, after independence it suffered a rapid decline in popularity and only remained in Oral (often called by the Russian name, "Uralsk"), where the country's only professional club Akzhaiyk is located.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] They presently compete in the Russian second tier division, the Russian Bandy Supreme League.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Recently bandy has started to gain popularity again outside of Oral, most notably in Petropavl and Khromtau.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Those were for example the three Kazakh cities which had players in the team at the Youth-17, Youth Bandy World Championship for boys in 2016.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The capital Astana has hosted national youth championships in rink bandy as well as championships in traditional eleven-a-side bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In recent years the former capital Almaty has hosted both the Asian Winter Games (with bandy on the program) as well as the Bandy World Championship for men in which Kazakhstan finished 3rd.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Plans are being made to reinvigorate the bandy section of the club Dynamo Almaty, who won the Soviet Championships in 1977 and 1990 as well as the European Cup in 1978.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Almaty is also the home of the headquarters of the Asian Bandy Federation.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Since bandy began regaining popularity and acceptance, the state has begun supporting bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Medeu in Almaty is the only arena with artificial ice.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] A second arena in Almaty was built for the World Championship 2012, but it was taken down afterwards.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Stadion Yunost in Oral was supposed to get artificial ice for the 2017–18 season.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] It got delayed but in 2018 it was officially ready for use.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The national team took a silver medal at the 2011 Asian Winter Games, which led to being chosen as the best Mongolian sport team of 2011.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Mongolia was proud to win the bronze medal of the B division at the 2017 Bandy World Championship after which the President of Mongolia, Tsakhiagiin Elbegdorj, held a reception for the team.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy as an organized sport was introduced to the Netherlands in the 1890s by Pim Mulier and the sport became popular.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] However, in the 1920s, the interest turned to ice hockey, but in contrast to other countries in central and western Europe, the sport has been continuously played in the Netherlands and since the 1970s, the country has become a member of FIB and games have been more formalised again.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The national team started to compete at the WCS in 1991.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] However, without a proper venue, only rink bandy is played within the country.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The national governing body is the Bandy Bond Nederland.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy as an organized sport was introduced to Norway in the 1910s.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Swedes contributed largely and clubs sprang up around the capital of Kristiania (present day Oslo).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Oslo, including neighbouring towns, is in the twenty-first century still the region where bandy enjoys most popularity in Norway.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In 1912 the Norwegians played their first National Championship, which was played annually up to 1940.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] During World War II, when Norway was occupied by Germany, illegal bandy was played in hidden places in forests, on ponds and lakes.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In 1943, 1944 and 1945, illegal championships were held.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In 1946 legal play resumed and still goes on in form of the Norwegian Bandy Premier League (*Eliteserien*).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] After World War II the number of teams rose, as well as attendance which regularly were in the thousands, but mild winters in the 1970s and 1980s shrunk the league, and in 2003 only five clubs (teams) fought out the 1st division with low attendance numbers and little media coverage.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] As of 2021 there are 10 teams in the Norwegian Bandy Premier League.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Norway's best result in the World Championship is a second place in 1965.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Norwegian bandy champion is decided each year by a play-off among the best teams in the Norwegian Bandy Premier League.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The first Norwegian bandy champions was decided in 1912 and the championship has been held almost every year since.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Until 1928, the championship was played as 7-a-side bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In Russia bandy is known as hockey with a ball or simply Russian hockey.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] A similar game became popular among the Russian nobility in the early 1700s, with the imperial court of Peter the Great playing a predecessor of modern bandy on Saint Petersburg's frozen Neva river.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Russians initially played this game using ordinary footwear with sticks made out of juniper wood, but it wasn't until later that ice skates were introduced.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy did not become popular among the masses throughout the Russian Empire until the second half of the 19th century.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The predecessor of the current Russian Bandy Federation was founded in 1898.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy is considered a national sport in Russia and is the only discipline to have official support of the Russian Orthodox Church.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Traditionally the Russians used a longer skate blade than other nations, giving them the advantage of skating faster.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] However, they would find it more difficult to turn quickly.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] A bandy skate has a longer blade than an ice hockey skate, and the "Russian skate" is even longer.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Though bandy was still played in the Soviet Union after the Russian Revolution, they did not partake in any international games for many decades.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] While agreements had previously been made to play friendlies against Sweden in the late 1940s, these plans had not come to fruition.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The bandy event at the 1952 Winter Olympics in Oslo, Norway, where men's bandy featured as a demonstration sport, was played without any Soviet team.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] However, the Soviets reconsidered their position following this competition.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] When the Federation of International Bandy was formed in 1955, with the Soviet Union as one of its founding members, the Russians largely adopted the international rules of the game developed in England in the 19th century, with one notable exception.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The other countries adopted the border which until then had only been used in Russia.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The men's Russian professional bandy league is called the Russian Bandy Super League.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Russian Bandy Supreme League is the second tier of men's Russian bandy, below the Russian Bandy Super League.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In Sweden, the Elitserien (literally, the "Elite League") is the highest bandy league in the country for men, while Bandyallsvenskan is the second division.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In Finland, the highest bandy league for men is the Bandyliiga.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In a similar fashion, Russia, along with Sweden, has emerged as one of the two dominant women's bandy nations internationally, regularly placing first or second at the premier international bandy competition for women, the Women's Bandy World Championship.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] He talked, among other things, about the need to give more support to Russian bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] It was the first time a head of state had accepted a meeting to talk about Russian bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Attending the meeting were also Minister of Sport, Tourism and Youth policy Vitaly Mutko and presidential adviser Igor Levitin.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The month after, Igor Levitin held a follow-up meeting.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Russian Bandy Super League is the top tier of the Russian bandy league system.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] It is professional and played every year.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The winner in the final becomes Russian champion.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] It is considered a continuation of the Soviet Union championship, which was played annually until the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Russian Cup has been played annually most years since 1937, originally called the Soviet Cup.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy as an organized sport was introduced to Sweden in 1895.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Swedish royal family, noblemen and diplomats were among the first players.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] While the original inspiration mainly came from England, there also were early exchanges with Germany and Russia.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy was taken up as one of the sports at the international Nordic Games held in Sweden semi-annually from 1901.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Swedish championships for men have been played annually since 1907 and Sweden was the first country to have an annual bandy league.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In the 1920s students played the game, then it spread across the country and became a largely middle-class sport.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The games could attract huge crowds of spectators in those days.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] After Slottsbrons IF won the Swedish championship in 1934 it became popular amongst workers in many smaller industrial towns and villages.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Where there was a bandy club the local factory corporation also usually sponsored the club to mutual benefit as a successful team led to good PR for the company.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy remains the main sport in many of these places.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In the mid-20th Century, bandy was the most popular spectator sport in Sweden, drawing huge crowds for most events and having bigger audiences than football or ice hockey.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] While not having the same numbers now, bandy is increasing the number of spectators in the 2020s, in contrast to many other sports.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy in Sweden is famous for its "culture" where both playing bandy and being a spectator requires great fortitude and dedication.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] A bandyportföljen is the classic accessory for spectating and is typically made of brown leather, well worn, and contains a warm drink in a thermos and/or a bottle of liquor.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy is most often played at outdoor arenas during winter time, so the need for spectators to carry flasks or thermoses of 'warming' liquid like glögg is a natural effect.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] With the sport moving indoors in recent decades and the arenas urging for non-alcoholic policies for the audiences, this tradition has partly changed, though not without opposition.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] A notable tradition is "annandagsbandy", bandy games played on Saint Stephen's Day (*annandagen* = ’the second day [of Christmas]’), which for many Swedes is an important Christmas season tradition and always draws bigger crowds than usual.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Elite League is the top tier of Swedish bandy and is fully professional.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] At the end of the season, a play-off is made to make out the two teams playing the final match for the Swedish Championship.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Final is played every year on the third Saturday of March.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] From 1991 to 2012, it was played at Studenternas Idrottsplats in Uppsala, often drawing crowds in excess of 20,000.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] One reason the play-off match was set in Uppsala is because of IFK Uppsala's success at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] IFK Uppsala won 11 titles in the Swedish Championships between 1907 and 1920, which made them the most successful bandy club in the entire country (now, however, the record is held by Västerås SK).
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] A contributing factor was also the poor quality of the ice at Söderstadion, where the finals were held from 1967 to 1989.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In 2013 and 2014 the final was played indoors in Friends Arena, the national stadium for football in Solna, Stockholm, with a retractable roof and a capacity of 50,000.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The first final at Friends Arena in 2013 drew a record crowd of 38,474 when Hammarby IF Bandy, after ending up in second place in six finals during the 2000s, won their second title.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Due to declining attendance from 2015 through 2017 Tele2 Arena in southern Stockholm was chosen as a new venue.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] However, the new indoor venue failed to attract much more than half of the total capacity.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In May 2017 it was announced that the finals will again be held at Studenternas IP in Uppsala from 2018 through at least 2021.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The *Svenska Cupen* (English: The Swedish Cup), *Svenska Cupen i bandy*, takes place exclusively in Sweden.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] It is a single-elimination tournament competition in Swedish bandy and the second-most prominent bandy competition which is open only to domestic Swedish teams, after the national championship.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The first women's competition was played in 2019.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In the late nineteenth and early 20th century, Switzerland had become a popular place for winter vacations and people went there from all over Europe.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Winter sports like skiing, sledding and bandy was played in Geneva and other towns.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Students from Oxford and Cambridge went to Switzerland to play each other – the predecessor of the recurring Ice Hockey Varsity Match was a bandy match played in St.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] This popularity for Swiss venues of winter sport may have been a reason, the European Championship was held there in 1913.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy has mainly been played as a recreational sport in Switzerland in the 2000s and 2010s.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] A Swiss men's national team was finally started up in 2017 and a Swiss women's national team made its international début in the 2018 Women's Bandy World Championship.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy was played in Ukraine when it was part of the Soviet Union.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] After independence in 1991, it took some years before organized bandy formed again, but Ukrainian champions have been named annually since 2012.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The first recorded games of what may be considered bandy on ice took place in The Fens during the great frost of 1813–1814, although it is probable that the game had already been played there in the previous century.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bury Fen Bandy Club from Bluntisham-cum-Earith, near St Ives, was the most successful team, said to have remained unbeaten for a hundred years until the winter of 1890–1891.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Charles Goodman Tebbutt of the Bury Fen Bandy Club was responsible for the first published rules of bandy in 1882, and also for introducing the game into the Netherlands and Sweden, as well as elsewhere in England where it became popular with cricket, rowing, and hockey clubs.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Tebbutt's homemade bandy stick can be seen in the Norris Museum in St Ives.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The first Ice Hockey Varsity Matches between Oxford University and Cambridge University were played to bandy rules, even if it was called hockey on the ice at the time.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] It is sometimes claimed that a national team for England won the European Bandy Championships in 1913, but that tournament likely never took place.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] While bandy is often thought to have been a popular sport in England in the decades around 1900, few records seem to have been kept.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] A statue of a bandy player, designed by Peter Baker, was erected at the village pond of Earith to commemorate the 200th anniversary of the first documented game in 2013.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In March 2004, Norwegian ex-player Edgar Malman invited two big clubs to play a rink bandy exhibition game in Streatham, London.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Russian Champions and World Cup Winner Vodnik met Swedish Champions Edsbyns IF in a match that ended 10–10.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In 2010 England became a Federation of International Bandy member.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The national federation is based in Cambridgeshire, the historical heartland.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The England Bandy Federation, was set up on 2 January 2017 at a meeting held in the historic old skaters public house, the Lamb and Flag in Welney in Norfolk, England, replacing the Bandy Federation of England which had been founded in 2010 but had had dwindling activity.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In September 2017, the federation decided to widen its territory to all of the United Kingdom and changed its name to Great Britain Bandy Association.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Great Britain entered a national team in the 2019 World Championships Group B in January and undefeated up to the final, won the silver medal in their final match against Estonia.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] They were set to return to the 2020 World Championships, but were refused visas to Russia.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] However, the comeback will come in 2025.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] In 2022, Great Britain premiered its national women's bandy team at the 2022 Women's Bandy World Championship.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy in its original, informal manner disappeared from the North American continent entirely once it and elements from the early game had become absorbed into a new sport of ice hockey.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] While ice hockey was growing and organizing in the United States, bandy was doing the same, but only in Europe and Scandinavia.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] It would not arrive in its organized format in the United States until the 1970s, almost a century after its initial development.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Bandy has been played in the United States since around the 1970s, after its promotion by Russians, Swedes and Finns in an exchange with softball, a sport which was promoted by Americans during the same time in the Soviet Union, Sweden and Finland.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] A key-person in the establishment of the sport in America was Bob Kojetin of Minnesota Softball.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The sport is centered in Minnesota, with very few teams based elsewhere.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The United States national bandy team has participated in the Bandy World Championships since 1985 and is also regularly playing friendly matches against Canada.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The leading organization for bandy in the US is USA Bandy.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The US has a men's national bandy team and a women's national bandy team.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The first bandy game in the US was played in December 1979 at the Lewis Park Bandy Rink in Edina, Minnesota.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] It was a friendly game between the Swedish junior national team and Swedish club team Brobergs IF.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] United States bandy championships have been played annually since the early 1980s, but the sport is not widely covered by American sports media.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The championship trophy is called the Gunnar Cup, named after Gunnar Fast, a Swedish army captain who helped introduce bandy to the United States around 1980.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] While North American ice hockey rinks can be used for playing the bandy variant of rink bandy, places where the traditional game of bandy can be played require a larger sized playing surface, a bandy field, and are almost non-existent in North America.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] Minnesota is home to the only regulation sized bandy "rink" in North America, the Guidant John Rose Minnesota Oval, commonly referred to as, "The Oval", and is also the largest outdoor refrigerated skating rink in North America.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The rink is 10,219 square meters with more than 800 tons of refrigeration and 135 km of pipes underneath the ice.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The ice can be maintained in temperatures up to +10 degrees Celsius.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Oval can hold up to 300 spectators and has hosted World Cup Speedskating, the 2016 Women's Bandy World Championship, and Aggressive Skating/Biking competitions.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The Oval is used mostly for inline hockey during the summer.
[src:defense-sports/bandy-p02] The following associations are the governing bodies for bandy in different countries and are member organizations of the Federation of International Bandy.
[src:defense-sports/defense-sports] In many team sports, **defense** (American spelling) or **defence** (Commonwealth spelling) is the action of preventing an opponent from scoring.
[src:defense-sports/defense-sports] The term may also refer to the tactics involved in defense, or a sub-team whose primary responsibility is defense.
[src:defense-sports/defense-sports] Similarly, a **defense player** or **defender** is a player who is generally charged with preventing the other team's forwards from being able to bear down directly on their own team's goalkeeper or goaltender.
[src:defense-sports/defense-sports] Such positions exist in association football, ice hockey, water polo and many other sports.
[src:defense-sports/defense-sports] In bat-and-ball sports, the defending team is in the field, while the offensive team sends only a few players into the field to try to score at a time.
[src:defense-sports/defense-sports] These sports generally involve a member of the defense throwing the ball to a member of the offensive team, who then tries to hit it and run to various safe areas of the field to score points.
[src:defense-sports/defense-sports] Failing to hit the ball properly, or failing to reach the safe areas before the ball is used against the offensive player, can result in that player being left unable to score.
[src:defense-sports/defense-sports] Baseball is unlike most other competitive sports in that the defense is given control of the ball.
[src:defense-sports/defense-sports] Additionally, the number of players on the field at any given time is lopsided in favor of the defense which always has nine players on the field; the offense has between one and four.
[src:defense-sports/defense-sports] Historically, each player on the team had a role both on offense and defense.
[src:defense-sports/defense-sports] Most amateur and professional leagues have adopted the designated hitter (DH) rule introduced by the American League of Major League Baseball.
[src:defense-sports/defense-sports] In leagues that use the DH, pitchers usually do not bat, and the DH bats in lieu of the pitcher and does not play a defensive position.
